<FIRST>r a AM-EspionageArrest     05-06 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Espionage Arrest,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unemployed Automobile Salesman Arrested on Espionage Complaint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Russian language specialist for the Air
Force 34-year-old was arrested Friday on espionage charges, accused
of trying to give U.S. military secrets to the Soviet Union.
   Ronald Craig Wolf, 34, was arrested without incident by the FBI
on a warrant charging him with gathering or delivering defense
information to aid a foreign government, authorities said.
   He was being held at Lew Sterrett Justice Center and was to
appear before a U.S. Magistrate, officials said. If convicted, Wolf
could face life imprisonment.
   The FBI said Wolf, formerly a Russian specialist for the Air
Force, never actually made contact with anyone from the Soviet
Union, but believed he was doing so when he handed over classified
materials to an undercover agent.
   Wolf, who worked occasionally as an automobile salesman, was
unemployed and living in a Dallas rooming house at the time of his
arrest, the FBI said.
   As a specialist who monitored and transcribed sensitive
communications, Wolf had been granted a ``Top Secret'' clearance
that gave him access to classified Air Force documents ``and
programs vital to the defense of the United States,'' according to
an affidavit by FBI special agent James W. Evans.
   Wolf was discharged from the Air Force in 1981, upon a
recommendation from superiors that he was financially irresponsible.
   In March, Wolf contacted someone he believed was a Soviet
undercover agent, but was actually an undercover FBI agent,
officials said. Over the course of five conversations, Wolf
allegedly discussed his military background and made it clear that
he would sell military secrets and also wanted to defect.
   According to the FBI, his motivation was not only money, but
also ``to get revenge for his treatment by the United States
government.''
   He later sent two letters containing material to a post office
box in Maryland, the FBI said. The material was later determined by
Air Force investigators to be sensitive information about Air Force
operations and programs.
</TEXT>
