<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-NorthTrial Bjt   05-06 0700</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial, Bjt,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors Said Trial Was Political Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreman of the Oliver North jury says the
jurors were caught in ``a war between the Democrats and the
Republicans'' and should have received the testimony of President
Bush and former President Reagan.
   Nevertheless, ``I think it was a fair trial,'' Denise Anderson,
34, told reporters at a news conference in her living room Friday,
24 hours after the jury convicted North of three Iran-Contra
charges and acquitted him of nine others.
   Asked whether the trial was fair even though Reagan was not
called to testify about the events that shook his second White
House term, Ms. Anderson said, ``It was fair to a certain degree.''
   ``I feel as though Reagan, and I could go on to elaborate on who
else, should have been down there,'' she said.
   She did not elaborate on who else, but when asked if she
included Bush, she replied, ``I'm not leaving him out.''
   Asked if she would like to have heard Reagan's testimony, Ms.
Anderson said: ``Yes, because he knew a lot about what was going
on.''
   Both Bush and Reagan have said they told investigators all they
knew about the Iran-Contra scandal, which occurred while Reagan was
president and Bush vice president.
   The defense subpoenaed both of them to testify, but Judge
Gerhardt Gesell quashed the subpoena. He cited court precedents
against requiring the testimony of a sitting president, and said
the defense had not shown that Reagan's testimony was needed.
   Documents in the trial suggested a bigger role for Bush than
revealed earlier concerning the solicitation of other countries'
support for the Contra rebels in Nicaragua at a time when U.S.
military aid for them was banned by law. But Bush, who visited
Honduras' president in early 1985, declared Thursday the meeting
had not been part of any deal to provide Honduras with expedited
U.S. aid in return for help for the rebels.
   Asked whether the trial was worth the money it cost, the jury
foreman said: ``I think in a way it was a waste of taxpayers'
money. I think it was a war going on, right here in our Congress. I
see it as a war between the Democrats and the Republicans.''
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater turned away
questions about a pardon for North, saying he asked Bush about it
and the president replied, ``I haven't discussed it with anybody.''
   Fitzwater said Bush preferred ``not to have any comment at this
time'' on the verdicts.
   North said Thursday he would appeal.
   Earl F. Williams, 65, an unemployed former security guard who
served on the jury, expressed sympathy for North, an ex-Marine who
served as a National Security Council aide in the Reagan White
House.
   ``I think in my heart that he thought he was doing the right
thing,'' Williams said. ``And I think there were people higher who
gave him authority to do a lot of things and then, when he got
caught out there high and dry, no one came to help him.''
   Ms. Anderson, a clerical worker at a hospital, said none of the
jurors favored convicting North on all counts ``because they (the
prosecution) didn't have the proof and the facts to back it up.''
But she said she believed North ``should do some time'' in prison
for the counts he was convicted of.
   North faces a maximum of 10 years plus a fine of up to $750,000.
Gesell said he would pass sentence on June 23.
   Asked if she was impressed with the testimony of North's
secretary, Fawn Hall, who broke down in tears as she defended her
former boss, Ms. Anderson said, ``No, at all.''
   ``All that crying she did down there ... She's just trying to
get a piece of the action,'' the jury foreman said.
   _Juror Tara King, 35, said in interviews that she had been using
cocaine until ``three or four months'' before the trial, but she
said it did not affect her work as a juror. King said she did not
tell the trial judge about her previous use of drugs because ``he
didn't ask me.''
</TEXT>
