<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearReform     05-06 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Reform,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latest Nuclear Controversy Renews Talk of Abolishing NRC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission's muted
response to revelations of ``silence-for-money'' deals between
nuclear plant builders and workers is fueling a drive on Capitol
Hill to replace the commission with a new agency.
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., plans to introduce a bill next week
that would dissolve the NRC and create a Nuclear Safety Agency,
Breaux aide Bob Mann said Friday.
   Unlike the five-member commission, the new agency would be
headed by a single administrator. It also would have an independent
board to investigate reactor safety problems.
   ``It's a long overdue change,'' said John Ahearne, an NRC member
for five years and its chairman from 1979-81.
   A similar bill in the last Congress easily passed the Senate but
died in the House.
   At a hearing Thursday on the silence-for-money issue, Breaux
said the commission's inability to agree on the legality and
acceptability of such deals was clear evidence that it should be
abolished in the best interests of the industry.
   ``The commission ... fails to send coherent and timely
regulatory signals to the nuclear industry and the public,'' Breaux
said. ``This must be changed.''
   Breaux slammed the commission for not publicly disavowing an
agreement signed by Brown &amp; Root, the builder of the Comanche Peak
nuclear plant in Texas, and a former electrician who claims he was
dismissed for questioning plant safety. The worker was paid
$15,000, plus $20,000 for his attorneys, in exchange for agreeing
to drop his complaints and not testify at NRC licensing hearings.
   Breaux said his subcommittee had evidence at least one other
such agreement existed between a builder and a worker. He said even
if these deals were legal, they hurt the nuclear industry by giving
at least the appearance of ``bribery.''
   Lando W. Zech Jr., the NRC chairman, said commission members
disagreed on the legality of such arrangements, and the commission
intended to study the matter further.
   Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., said it already was clear the NRC had
outlived its usefulness.
   ``It doesn't work, it never has, and we had better jettison it
...,'' Simpson said.
   The main beefs against the commission are that it is slow to act
and that its members are too cozy with the utilities whose plants
must be licensed by the NRC.
   When the NRC was created in 1974 as part of legislation that
abolished the Atomic Energy Commission, the purpose was to separate
the regulators from those in government who were promoting the
peaceful uses of nuclear energy. Critics in recent years have said
the NRC is too vulnerable to promotional influences.
   A 1984 report by the non-profit Union of Concerned Scientists,
assessing the NRC's first decade, said its lack of skepticism about
the nuclear industry had ``blinded the agency to fundamental safety
defects'' that hurt the industry and consumers.
   Plans to replace the NRC with an agency headed by a single
administrator _ along the lines of the Environmental Protection
Agency _ have been proposed, but died, many times in the past. The
nuclear utility companies have opposed the legislation.
   Mann said Breaux's bill, co-sponsored by Simpson, will include
these main provisions:
   _Abolish the commission and establish the Nuclear Safety Agency,
headed by an administrator appointed by the president and subject
to confirmation by the Senate.
   _Create an office of inspector general, headed by a presidential
appointee, to investigate allegations of wrongdoing within the
agency. A separate office of investigations would probe possible
wrongdoing at nuclear plants.
   _Create a safety investigations board to conduct independent
investigations of significant safety problems at licensed nuclear
facilities.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
