<FIRST>r w PM-Grain-Soviets     05-06 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Grain-Soviets,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Sales Made Under New Subsidized Grain Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five companies have sold wheat to the Soviet
Union under the new subsidized grain deal announced by President
Bush.
   In all, the Agriculture Department is expected to approve
subsidies on 1.5 million metric tons of wheat destined to the
Soviet Union. The first 300,000 tons were announced on Friday.
   Christopher E. Goldthwait, acting general sales manager for the
department's Foreign Agricultural Service, said the sales by five
exporting companies call for shipment later this month.
   Goldthwait said the subsidies averaged $8.46 per ton, or about
23 cents per bushel of wheat. The total for the 300,000 tons would
be about $2.5 million.
   The Soviet Union had bought more than 4 million tons of U.S.
wheat for 1988-89 delivery at prices subsidized under the
department's Export Enhancement Program, or EEP, but the previous
authorization had virtually run out with the last sale March 13.
   Bush, under pressure from USDA and farm-state members of
Congress, announced a new authorization on May 2 of 1.5 million
tons, half of what had been sought. However, according to wheat
people and others, the Soviets agreed to buy an additional 1.5
million tons of wheat later in the summer at regular market prices.
   Members of Congress want the Bush administration, including the
Office of Management and Budget, to clarify the role of the subsidy
program and to explain why there has been a slowdown in new
authorizations.
   In addition to the wheat, USDA said the Soviet Union bought an
additional 200,000 tons of corn for delivery during the current
marketing year, which runs through Sept. 30.
   The latest sales brought to a record 19.1 million tons the total
corn and wheat sales to the Soviet Union for delivery this year
under terms of the long-term supply agreement between the two
countries. The old mark of 18.6 million tons shipped to the Soviets
was reached in 1984-85.
   Corn, which is not subsidized, makes up almost 15 million tons
of the current total, with wheat at 4.13 million tons. In addition,
the Soviets have bought 450,000 tons of soybeans, 1.37 million tons
of soybean meal, and 757,400 tons of grain sorghum.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 300,000 tons of
wheat would be about 11 million bushels, and the 200,000 tons of
corn about 7.9 million bushels.
   Wheat prices have been averaging about $4.15 per bushel at the
farm level, according to the latest USDA five-day average, meaning
that the latest sale could have a farm value of around $46 million.
   The corn sale, at around $2.56 per bushel, would have a current
farm value of $20 million.
   Under EEP arrangements, private exporters can sell U.S.
commodities at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition
in selected overseas markets and then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other commodities as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Goldthwait said the new subsidized wheat sales were handled by
Ferruzzi USA Inc., 50,000 tons; Central States Enterprises Inc.,
50,000; Peavey Co., 120,000; Union Equity Exchange, 50,000; and
Richco Grain Ltd., 30,000.
   The identities of firms selling corn or other commodities not
awarded USDA subsidies are not disclosed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
