<FIRST>r w PM-North-Pension     05-06 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North-Pension,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Will Keep Pension at Least Until After Sentencing</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-North Trial Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North will keep his Marine Corps
pension, at least until he's sentenced on June 23.
   The corps, in a brief statement, said Friday it wanted to
correct reports that North's pension already had been stopped.
   North, a retired lieutenant colonel and former Natioal Security
Council aide, was convicted Thursday of three felony counts
stemming from the Iran-Contra affair.
   On Thursday, the Marine Corps said one of those three felonies _
destroying NSC documents _ was sufficient to cost him his military
pension of roughly $23,100 a year.
   On Friday, however, the corps said North's conviction would have
to be reviewed by military lawyers and his sentencing completed
before any other steps were taken.
</TEXT>
