<DOCNO> AP890506-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Osprey     05-06 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Osprey,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Won't Give Reprieve to Osprey Builders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department is standing firm in its
decision to cancel the V-22 Osprey weapon program, and is warning
the two companies working on the project to honor their current
contract.
   The two companies, in turn, said Friday they had decided against
laying off employees and promised they would keep working with
sympathetic members of Congress to win more money for the
tilt-rotor aircraft.
   The current contract with Bell Helicopter Textron Inc. and the
Boeing Helicopter Co. expires Sept. 30, the end of fiscal year 1989.
   ``We expect them to honor their commitments,'' said Lt. Cmdr.
Jim Kudla, a Pentagon spokesman. ``Our position on this program has
not changed.''
   The two companies had warned the Pentagon they considered Friday
the deadline for receiving a commitment of additional federal
dollars.
   But a Bell spokesman, Terry Arnold, announced late in the day
the two companies had suspended their threat of layoffs for the
moment.
   ``Pleased with strong bipartisan congressional support for the
V-22 program, Bell-Boeing officials said today they're continuing
to meet with senior Defense Department management, seeking their
support for the Osprey tilt-rotor program,'' Arnold said.
   ``Bell-Boeing has reached no decision on a future course of
action at this time. We are continuing to work on the program.''
   Another company official, who asked not to be named, told The
Associated Press the contractors were still hopeful of getting more
money from the Pentagon.
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney, in fashioning a fiscal 1990
military budget to honor a White House-Congress budget compromise,
last week announced $10 billion in cuts to the original spending
plan of the Reagan administration.
   In making those cuts, Cheney ordered the Osprey program canceled
outright, saying the Pentagon simply couldn't afford the plane and
that the Marine Corps could do just as well by ordering additional
_ and cheaper _ helicopters.
   The Pentagon had planned to spend $25.9 billion on 663 Ospreys,
including $1.3 billion in 1990. The department has already invested
$2 billion in the program over a nine-year period.
   One senior defense official, who likewise insisted on anonymity,
declared: ``The decision has been made that there's not going to be
any more money.''
   The V-22 Osprey, described by the Marine Corps as its most
important weapon program, is a revolutionary aircraft designed to
take off like a helicopter and fly like an airplane. To do this, it
utilizes special propellers at the tip of each wing that can swivel
upward and back.
   The Marine Corps wants to use the planes to improve its ability
to conduct surprise, long-range amphibious assaults. The first of
the planes just recently began flight tests in Texas.
   The problem facing Bell-Boeing is that the contractors already
have received all the Pentagon money due them under their fiscal
1989 development contract and are experiencing overruns. Thus in
order to continue work on a program that Cheney has vowed to kill
on Oct. 1, the companies would have to sink their own money into
the project for the next five months.
   The Pentagon has estimated the overruns at roughly $25 million a
month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
