<FIRST>r i PM-Panama-Fraud     05-06 0813</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Fraud,0840</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fraud Becomes Main Issue in Panama Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charges of fraud and U.S. meddling
have replaced Panama's social and economic problems as the main
issues in Sunday's presidential election.
   A three-party coalition hoping to unseat the government and its
de facto leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, claims a substantial
lead in polls but charges the government plans to steal the
election.
   The strongly anti-American government has trumpeted reports that
the CIA funneled $10 million to the opposition campaign. Washington
declines to comment on the reports, which the opposition denies.
   Noriega is not a candidate, but the election is seen as a
referendum on his rule since he assumed control of Panama's defense
forces in 1985.
   Voters cast ballots Sunday for a president, two vice presidents,
67 legislators and hundreds of local officers.
   A recent poll by the Civil Opposition Alliance gave its own
presidential candidate, Guillermo Endara, a lead of 58 percent to
26 percent for government-backed Carlos Duque.
   ``The information we have is that the government polls show them
to be worse off than ours do,'' said Willy Cochez, vice president
of the alliance's Christian Democratic Party.
   The government has not published its polls.
   Cochez said alliance supporters have discovered attempts to rig
the election.
   ``We have detected about 60,000 cedulas (voter identification
cards) with the same numbers but different names on them,'' Cochez
said in an interview. Between 150,000 and 200,000 cards were
duplicated, meaning hundreds of thousands of the 1.1 million
registered voters can vote more than once, he claimed.
   Cochez also said pro-government activists are visiting houses
that display opposition symbols and offering to buy voters' cards.
   ``There may be five people who can vote in the house and they
are offered $50 each. If the family is poor it might not ever see
that much money at one time again. What is this person to do?''
Cochez asked.
   Government officials frequently told opposition voters seeking
cards that the camera for identification photographs was broken or
that there was no film, said Cochez. ``All lies,'' he added.
   The U.S. government also predicts fraud. American officials are
discussing not who will win but what they should do in the face of
the expected vote manipulation.
   ``The polls are so bad that (Noriega) will have to steal it big
time,'' said Rep. Pat Schroeder, D-Colo.
   Noriega was indicted by two federal grand juries in Miami last
year on drug-trafficking charges, charges he denies. Then-President
Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire him, but was ousted himself by
Noriega.
   The United States has frozen $140 million in Panamanian bank
deposits and canal payments, hobbling the banking industry and
leaving the government ill-equipped to meet payrolls or fund basic
social programs.
   Such sanctions hit hard in a country where one in every eight
workers has a government job, and the government relies heavily on
the poor and the public sector for support.
   Government officials say the election will be clean and legal
but acknowledged Sunday that was not always the case.
   ``We must not repeat ... the phenomenon of the elections of
1984, in which the National Tabulation Board, in a sad omissconsequences
could be described as deadly to the image of the
Electoral Tribunal,'' tribunal president Yolanda Pulice de
Rodriguez said Sunday.
   He was referring to the ``victory'' of Nicolas Ardito Barletta
in 1984 after the government stopped the vote count.
   Pro-government newspapers have played heavily on reports of the
alleged $10 million CIA donation to the opposition, which has
access to some radio stations, but whose press Noriega closed more
than a year ago.
   ``The $10 million is only the part that we know about,'' acting
President Manuel Solis Palma told a cheering crowd in the Atlantic
coastal city of Colon last week. ``We have information that it
could be more.''
   Guillermo Ford, one of two opposition vice presidential
candidates, retorted: ``We don't need money from anybody to run our
campaign.''
   The reports gave some credence to government charges that the
United States wants to reduce Panama to a colony, invade militarily
and renege on the 1977 Panama Canal Treaties, which give Panama
control of the canal in 2000.
   For the government, the charges could not have come at a better
time, enlivening a dull campaign. But many Panamanians say the
election will not solve their country's problems. Noriega has
survived everything the opposition and the United States have been
able to throw at him.
   ``It doesn't matter who wins, the future will remain
uncertain,'' said Carmen Black, a 26-year-old housewife.
   ``People are afraid, and a lot of people aren't going to vote,''
said 40-year-old publicist Sara Villamonte.
</TEXT>
