<NOTE>Eds: Version of following item moved on sports wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavyweight boxing champion Mike Tyson may
be undefeated in the ring, but he's 0-2 against Albany police, who
issued the champ his second speeding ticket in nine days.
   Tyson, whose career began in nearby Catskill, was ticketed
Friday morning for speeding in his 1989 Lamborghini, said police
Sgt. Robert Wolfgang.
   Wolfgang said a police officer spotted Tyson's car and another
vehicle exceeding the 30 mph speed limit.
   ``It was not a clocked situation, but the officer determined
they were driving at a greater speed than is prudent for the
traffic conditions,'' Wolfgang said.
   Tyson and the other driver are scheduled to appear May 23 in
Albany Traffic Court, Wolfgang said.
   Police issued Tyson a speeding ticket on April 26 for driving 71
mph.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Literacy volunteers have their work cut out for
them, says first lady Barbara Bush.
   ``The child whose parents can't read has a little tougher time
than one whose can,'' Mrs. Bush told about 50 volunteers on Friday.
``So you're going to teach the parents to read, and everybody's
going to be better off for it.''
   Mrs. Bush said the creation of the Dallas County Adult Literacy
Council is an important step toward fighting illiteracy.
   The new council, which released figures to show that one of five
adults in Dallas County needs literacy training, will serve as an
information, assistance and referral agency.
   ``I hope today will mark the beginning of a renewed effort for
literacy in Dallas, one that will involve everyone _ educators,
volunteers, civic leaders and businesses,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GURNEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Elvis was the King of Rock 'n' Roll,
Linda Jones fancies herself the queen.
   ``I see my life, I see Elvis' life, and I feel there is a
connection,'' said Ms. Jones, 41, whose curling lip, jet-black hair
and high cheekbones are reminiscent of the rock 'n' roll legend.
   ``Ever since I was little, it was always Elvis with me. I'm a
big believer in fate,'' she said.
   Ms. Jones is hoping fate will intervene this weekend when she
auditions in Las Vegas for a showman who launched a nationwide
search for a female Elvis.
   If she impresses the directors as much in person as she did in
an audition videotape, Ms. Jones would be the only female in a show
whose other cast members are men impersonating women.
   Wearing Elvis-style jumpsuits and black sunglasses, and
swiveling her hips, Ms. Jones could easily pass for Presley in his
prime _ until she opens her mouth to sing.
   That's why she lip-syncs Elvis hits like ``Hound Dog'' and
``Don't Be Cruel.''
   Ms. Jones said she's not sure she'd leave her life in Gurnee for
the glitz and glamour of Las Vegas.
   ``Elvis is important to me and my act is important to me,'' Ms.
Jones said. ``I mean, I'd like to do this professionally and all,
but I don't want to give up my whole act for it.
   ``I'm not into this for the money. I love Elvis,'' she said,
tapping her heart, ``from here.''
