<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Foreign 1stLd-Writethru a0409 05-06 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Foreign, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0409,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Stands Firm on Short-Range Weapons After Talk With Kohl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf pvs, bgng The White, to correct date of Paris
summit; picks up 5th graf, Over the</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House says President Bush and West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl have failed in their latest round of
long-distance diplomacy to resolve major differences over nuclear
weapons in Europe.
   Bush and Kohl spoke by telephone for 20 minutes Friday about the
West German's proposal to soon open East-West talks on eliminating
short-range nuclear weapons in Europe. The White House said Bush
was unchanged in his opposition to such negotiations.
   The Bush-Kohl conversation came amid a flurry of developments on
other foreign policy fronts. In other news:
   _The White House announced Bush will visit Poland and Hungary in
July before going to the annual seven-nation economic summit in
Paris, to be held July 14-16. He will be the first president to
visit Eastern Europe since 1977. From Paris, Bush will travel
elsewhere in Europe, probably stopping in Portugal and the
Netherlands.
   _Over the objections of Panama, Bush named a 14-person
commission to observe what he predicts will be fraudulent elections
there Sunday. The observers, led by Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., leave
today and fly to a U.S. air base in Panama to avoid that nation's
visa requirements.
   _U.S. officials said Secretary of State James A. Baker III will
propose to the Soviet Union next week that negotiations to sharply
reduce strategic nuclear weapons be resumed in June in Geneva. He
will suggest that the talks pick up where they left off in November.
   The dispute between Bonn and Washington on short-range nuclear
weapons _ missiles and artillery shells _ threatens to mar the
harmony of a NATO summit scheduled May 29-30 in Brussels.
   The United States opposes any negotiations on grounds that NATO
needs nuclear weapons to compensate for the overwhelming
superiority of Soviet-bloc tanks, artillery, soldiers and other
conventional forces.
   ``The United States posture has not changed,'' White House press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said after the telephone call. ``It does
not appear that a basis for agreement is there, but we'll continue
to discuss it and see.''
   Fitzwater said, ``We would like to reach an agreement before the
NATO summit, but if we can't, it's not the end of the world.''
   ``We'll go to the summit and we'll discuss it there,'' he added.
``If we don't get an agreement at the summit, then we'll go on and
discuss it after the summit.''
   The spokesman voiced sharp skepticism about peace initiatives
proposed by Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev and said the
Soviets are seeking to exploit the current NATO rift.
   ``The Soviets have worked assiduously to try to divide the
alliance,'' Fitzwater said. ``General Secretary Gorbachev has made
any number of proposals trying to convince people that there is no
longer a threat from the Soviet Union. And we are very wary of that
approach.''
   In Vienna, Soviet and East German diplomats used Friday's
resumption of East-West talks on conventional weapons to emphasize
Warsaw Pact support for parallel talks on reducing short-range
nuclear weapons.
   East German Ambassador Klaus-Dieter Ernst insisted such
negotiations are vital to Germans, telling a news conference: ``The
shorter the range of the rockets, the more dead Germans.''
   The Bush administration wants to modernize the aging arsenal of
Lance missiles clustered in Western Europe, most of them in West
Germany.
   Of Friday's Bush-Kohl phone conversation, Fitzwater said, ``I
would not characterize it as moving the situation one way or
another.''
   Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland, who met with
Bush this week, predicted a solution would be found at the summit
that links cuts in conventional and short-range nuclear arms agreed
on by the allies last year.
   Speaking at the National Press Club, Brundtland said Friday,
``We can negotiate for lower levels both in conventional and
short-range (weapons), and I do think it is possible to reach
common ground on that basis.''
</TEXT>
