<FIRST>r a PM-DisneySplash     05-06 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Disney Splash,0277</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anxious Riders Will Have to Wait For Splash Mountain Flume Ride</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Months of delays in opening Splash
Mountain, Disneyland's newest attraction, have left park executives
all wet and visitors disappointed.
   The nine-minute ride is designed around the adventures of Br'er
Rabbit and includes a 52{-foot plunge down a flume pitched at a
45-degree angle. It was to have opened in January, but officials
feared it packed too much splash and delayed the debut while
workers toned down the big dive.
   ``I got soaking wet one day and had to get out and change
clothes,'' said Tony W. Baxter, the ride's executive producer, who
has tested the ride.
   Engineers have redesigned the ride's log boats, trimming their
capacity from eight passengers to seven and replacing their heavy
shells with lighter fiberglass.
   The ride is likely to open this summer, although no date has
been set, spokesman Bob Roth said Friday.
   ``I think there's an expectation with Disneyland that the
quality will be top-notch. You may get a little wet but not
soaked,'' said Roth.
   Aaron Kreitzer, a 17-year-old visitor from Portland, Ore., was
disappointed to find the ride still closed. ``We heard it was going
to be open from the pilot on the plane coming down,'' he said.
   The delay also has disappointed McDonald's Corp. and Coca-Cola
Co. Both companies scheduled promotions to coincide with the
expected January opening and found out about the delays too late to
postpone the promotions.
   ``Obviously, we would have liked it if it could have opened as
planned,'' said Greg Hogan, a regional manager for McDonald's.
</TEXT>
