<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Heller     05-06 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Heller,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Cancer Institute Director Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHESDA, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. John Roderick Heller Jr., former
director of the National Cancer Institute and a former president of
the Memorial-Sloan Kettering Cancer in New York, has died. He was
84.
   Heller died on Thursday at Suburban Hospital outside Washington,
D.C., after a stroke.
   A specialist in cancer research, he directed the National Cancer
Institute at the National Institutes of Health from 1948 until
1960. He then became president and chief executive officer of the
Memorial-Sloan Kettering center, but retired three years later
after suffering a stroke.
   Heller recieved the Eleanor Roosevelt Cancer Foundation's first
annual World Peace Through World Health Award from President John
F. Kennedy 1961 and was profiled by Time magazine in a 1959 cover
story on cancer research.
   He retired to Bethesda in 1965 and worked as a consultant to the
American Cancer Society and the National Cancer Institute.
   Heller was born in Fair Play, S.C. He graduated from Clemson
College in 1925 and from Emory University Medical School in 1929.
   He worked for the U.S. Public Health Service in Little Rock,
Brunswick, Ga., Nashville, Tuskeegee, Ala., Boston and Harrisburg,
Pa. before becoming chief of the service's venereal disease
division in 1943.
</TEXT>
