<FIRST>r a PM-FBI-HispanicsPlaintiff Bjt   05-06 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FBI-Hispanics Plaintiff, Bjt,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hispanic FBI Agents Say Discrimination Ruling Was Hard-won Fight</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY E. LANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI agent who sued the bureau for
denying him promotions believes the door is open for him and other
Hispanics to advance, but Bernardo M. ``Mat'' Perez concedes the
door had to be kicked down.
   ``We, Hispanics, as any other American citizens, have a
contribution to make and we want to believe in the American
system,'' he said after a federal judge ordered changes in the
agency's promotional system and established a procedure for
promoting Hispanics wrongly denied advancement.
   ``All we want is an equal chance. Now we're going to get it.''
   Because Hispanics do the same jobs as other FBI agents, they
deserve to obtain management positions, the 25-year veteran said.
   U.S. District Judge Lucius Bunton, after ruling in September
that the FBI discriminated against Hispanics, ordered a special
panel to be appointed to evaluate the claims of other Hispanic
agents in the class-action suit that they lost promotions.
   Perez, the No. 2 agent in El Paso and the agency's
second-highest ranking Hispanic, filed suit in 1987 after a series
of demotions and fruitless internal complaints about his treatment.
Formerly agent in charge in San Juan, Puerto Rico, he was dropped
to assistant agent in charge in Los Angeles.
   There, he claimed, agent in charge Richard Bretzing disliked him
because he was Hispanic.
   When Perez testified against Richard Miller, the only FBI agent
ever convicted of espionage, Bretzing accused Perez of committing
perjury and forced him to transfer to El Paso, a place Perez says
the FBI considers a ``dumping ground.''
   Perez thinks he would have been an FBI executive assistant
director if he had not been discriminated against. ``I think I can
do a lot more than I've been doing here for the past few years in
El Paso,'' he said.
   More than 300 Hispanic agents eventually joined the class-action
suit. Because of Friday's ruling, the FBI must promote Perez to the
next level in the bureau within 45 days.
   Additionally, FBI Director William S. Sessions must report to
the court every 90 days on promotional decisions regarding Perez
until the agent becomes a special agent in charge or is named to a
job with similar responsibilities.
   Perez said the promotion is a small one and won't affect his
salary, already at the top level.
   ``I was not held back money-wise and that was not my
contention,'' he said. ``I was not promoted within the FBI.''
   Bunton denied any monetary damages to Perez, who claimed more
than $600,000 in back pay and for damages for retaliation against
him by the FBI.
   In December, Bunton ruled the agency had misused a federal grand
jury subpoena to investigate Perez in retaliation for filing the
suit.
   And Perez said he may see more retaliation result from the
latest ruling.
   ``I would not be surprised if it comes,'' he said. ``I hope
(Sessions) will look upon it as a challenge. His friend, Judge
Bunton, has tried to be non-intrusive.''
   Before he was named FBI director in 1987, Sessions was a federal
judge in the western district of Texas and a colleague of Bunton.
   Despite discrimination and retaliation, Perez said he does not
blame Sessions for the racial problems within the FBI.
   ``I think he was given a bag by former Director (William)
Webster,'' Perez said. ``(Webster) put this system in place.''
</TEXT>
