<FIRST>r p PM-TexasMayoralRdp     05-06 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texas Mayoral Rdp,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayoral Candidates Wrap Up Campaigns In Texas Cities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in Texas today were choosing mayors in four
cities, three where it was expected to be no contest, and in El
Paso, where six candidates were vying to replace volatile
millionaire Jonathan Rogers.
   Incumbents in Dallas and Fort Worth were virtually assured
re-election and a former mayor was expecting to return to the post
in San Antonio.
   Political observers in El Paso were anticipating a runoff in the
race for Rogers' seat. Rogers, who served four, two-year terms, is
prevented by law from seeking a fifth.
   City Council members Suzie Azar and Ed Elsey and state Rep. Paul
Moreno were the favorites to advance to a May 27 runoff. Ms. Azar
has won the endorsement of the border city's two newspapers.
   Some candidates passed out campaign literature and shook hands
with voters amid rush-hour traffic in El Paso Friday, the most
vigorous activity at the end of a low-key campaign season.
   In Dallas, Mayor Annette Strauss and her leading challenger,
attorney Peter Lesser, attended Cinco de Mayo festivities.
   A poll last week showed Strauss was favored by 53 percent of
those surveyed. Lesser, who leads a pack of three challengers, was
next with 6 percent, according to the poll for The Dallas Morning
News. But the poll also found 37 percent were undecided.
   ``We think it's going to be a horse race,'' Kevin Kennedy, a
spokesman for Lesser's campaign, said Friday. ``We think we're
going to surprise a lot of people. There's definitely anti-Strauss
people out there. It's going to come down to who gets their forces
out.''
   In San Antonio, former Mayor Lila Cockrell led a field of seven
candidates.
   ``The absentee turnout was really low and we're trying to send
out messages that we need to get the vote out,'' said Ms.
Cockrell's campaign spokeswoman, Stacy McGhee. ``Ms. Cockrell feels
it will be a victory if there is a good turnout.''
   ``My guess is that the smaller the turnout the better it is for
me,'' said Carl Mauthe, an insurance executive who is considered
Ms. Cockrell's main opposition for the seat.
   Ms. Cockrell was mayor of the city from 1975 to 1981, preceding
current Mayor Henry Cisneros, who decided last year against running
for a fifth term.
   In Fort Worth, Mayor Bob Bolen was participating in his third
straight election without strong opposition. One candidate opposing
Bolen, Carlos Adams, had raised no money for the campaign during
the first three months of the year. A second candidate, Evelyn
Thomas Williams, did not file a campaign contribution report for
the period.
</TEXT>
