<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0255EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ABA-Judges Bjt   05-06 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ABA-Judges, Bjt,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABA, Thornburgh Feud Over Judicial Screening</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is
threatening to end the American Bar Association's role in screening
prospective federal judges unless it agrees not to consider
political or ideological beliefs.
   The ABA's Standing Committee on Federal Judiciary would no
longer screen prospective nominees unless the bar group keeps a
commitment that it made to made to Thornburgh, says David Runkel, a
senior aide to the attorney general.
   The ABA denies it made such a commitment.
   As he left the Justice Department on Friday night, Thornburgh
said ``we expect them to honor'' an agreement to revert to pre-1980
language in the ABA's judicial screening guidelines.
   The 1977 version does not contain any exception to the statement
that political and ideological views are not considered.
   Subsequent versions of the guidelines contain an exception that
such views are considered if they bear on the candidate's ability
to be a fair, impartial and open-minded judge.
   It is this language that Thornburgh and others cite as evidence
that the ABA has been using political and ideological views as
yardsticks for a candidate's fitness for the federal bench.
   The ABA says it never agreed to what Thornburgh described in
testimony Tuesday to the House Judiciary Committee. The dispute
broke out that day when ABA leaders took issue with Thornburgh's
statement.
   The Justice Department fired back on Friday.
   Runkel said the screening panel would be allowed to resume its
traditional role of helping the president screen prospective
judicial candidates ``as soon as the statement made by the attorney
general to the House Judiciary Committee is .... accepted by the
ABA.'' Runkel said.
   In a statement Friday night, ABA President Robert Raven
reiterated the bar group's position that the ``federal judicial
committee does not examine and make value judgments about
candidates' political or ideological views.''
   ``Problems of wording and problems of perception are curable,''
Raven said. ``We look forward to working out mutually acceptable
language with the attorney general.''
   Thorburgh replied: ``They got our language, go back to what it
was in 1979. That's what they agreed to and we expect them to honor
it.''
   The issue is especially ticklish for Thornburgh because his
choice for deputy attorney general, Robert B. Fiske Jr., has come
under fire from some conservative Republicans for the role he
played chairing the Standing Committee from 1984 to 1987.
   Sen. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., charges that Fiske leaked the
names of prospective nominees the panel received from the White
House to a liberal advocacy group.
   The advance information, Humphrey charges, enabled the group to
mount campaigns against individuals even before their candidates
were nominated.
   In apparent attempt to mollify Humphrey and others, Thornburgh
credited Fiske with negotiating the ``agreement'' when he made his
announcement to the House committee.
   The ABA's involvement in judicial screening, which dates back to
the Eisenhower administration, has become a heated one for
conservatives since the 1987 Senate vote against confirming Robert
Bork to the Supreme Court.
   Four members of the bar panel found Bork unqualified and Harold
R. Tyler Jr., the panel's chairman, explained at the time the
dissenters were concerned about what they regarded as Bork's
``comparatively extreme views'' on constitutional issues.
   The Senate Judiciary Committee has planned to hold hearings on
the whole issue of the ABA's involvement in judicial screening,
including the ratings it announces during confirmation proceedings.
   Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., the panel's chairman, Friday
postponed the May 11 hearing so that it would not conflict with
Thornburgh's schedule. Thornburgh is now expected to testify, along
with representatives of the ABA and interest groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
