<FIRST>r a PM-TankerSpill     05-06 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tanker Spill,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Oil Spill Cleanup Chief Wants More Effort From Exxon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's personal emissary at the
Alaska oil spill told Exxon to hasten its cleanup and said the
company should put a lot more people to work scrubbing the
oil-tainted shores.
   Adm. Paul A. Yost Jr., the commandant of the Coast Guard and the
ranking federal official in the oil spill zone, also said Friday
that Exxon's May 10 deadline to have the worst of the cleanup
completed on five islands in Prince William Sound may be in
jeopardy.
   A beach at Smith Island, one of the five targeted islands, ``is
not yet anywhere near clean,'' he said. ``I can't see when it will
be clean. It may be that we have to bypass that beach for two or
three weeks and then return to it.''
   Contamination on the islands is of special concern to state
officials and environmentalists, who fear the annual seal pupping
cycle may be affected.
   ``What I said to Exxon this morning is that they are going to
have to produce a significantly greater effort,'' the admiral said,
adding that Exxon should also expand its beach cleanup to areas
outside Prince William Sound.
   ``How many people?'' Yost said. ``I'm not ready to give them a
number yet.''
   Exxon has about 4,900 people involved in the cleanup effort,
according to figures supplied by the oil company and the state.
   The tanker Exxon Valdez struck a charted reef in the sound on
March 24, spilling more than 10 million gallons of crude. The
captain, Joseph Hazelwood of Huntington, N.Y., has been accused of
operating the vessel while drunk and he faces trial June 20 in
Valdez. An Alaska grand jury has also begun a felony investigation
into Hazelwood's role in the accident.
   Hazelwood's attorney said Friday the fired tanker captain was
not drunk when he left the vessel in command of his third mate
prior to the shipwreck.
   The oil has moved about 500 miles southwest of Valdez, fouling
the shore at several sites, including the Katmai National Park
wildlife refuge.
   ``I'd like to state right now for the people of Alaska, we don't
have hundreds of miles of heavily impacted beaches outside of
Prince William Sound,'' Yost said.
   Yost must approve Exxon's cleanup plan before it goes into
effect, but said he has not yet made a decision.
   Earlier this week, Yost criticized the revised plan, which Exxon
submitted May 1, as poorly drafted and lacking in specifics. The
state also has criticized it and urged extensive changes. But on
Friday, he called the plan ``workable ... but it needs expansion.''
   ``Some of the cleanup is difficult to the point that one wonders
if restoration will ever be possible,'' Yost said.
   ``Restoration will probably be done by the Lord in the next few
years. I don't think restoration is going to be done by Exxon in
the next few months on all of the beaches,'' he said. ``It's not
possible.''
   Under Exxon's proposal, 364 miles of coastline would be cleansed
by Sept. 15, although nearly 200 of those miles may be left
untouched _ to be scoured by wind and wave action. The worst of the
spill damage in Prince William Sound is to be cleaned by May 10,
according to the plan.
   The proposal seeks to dispose of waste by burying it, burning it
or discharging it through a wastewater treatment plant in Valdez.
The company has asked for permission to bypass some environmental
laws in order to dispose of the wastes.
</TEXT>
