<HEAD>Tourist Plane Lands in Jungle Near Cancun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tourist plane carrying up to 17
Americans was forced to make an emergency landing Friday afternoon
in the jungles of the Yucatan peninsula after an engine failed,
rescuers and reporters said.
   There were no immediate reports of deaths or injuries and it was
not immediately clear if the three-engine British-made Trislander
crashed while trying to land.
   The Aerocozumel plane flying from the archeological site of
Chichen Itza to the island resort of Cozumel made an emergency
landing about two miles outside the Playa del Carmen airport, about
15 miles south of Cancun.
   The Excelsior news agency said the aircraft, which was filled to
capacity and had one pilot, landed after one of its engines went
out. It said all passengers were believed to be American.
   While the jungle terrain hampered rescue operations, authorities
managed to air-drop food and medicine.
   Cmdr. Agustin Ortega Martin del Campo, army commander for the
region about 900 miles east of Mexico City, said a helicopter
reached the plane but was unable to land because of jungle growth.
   Speaking by telephone from Cancun, he said about 30 Mexican
soldiers were going overland to the site but were slowed by the
jungle terrain and lack of nearby roads.
   Diego Acosta, commander of the Red Cross in Cancun, said
military crews were cutting a route through the jungle to reach the
plane.
   He said the helicopter that overflew the site said there was no
fire.
   There had been no contact with the people aboard, he said.
</TEXT>
