<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0407EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-SecondAbduction     05-06 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Second Abduction,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police: Parents Are Chief Suspects In Second Child's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state has taken custody of a couple's
15-month-old son while the pair is investigated in the death of a
daughter they reported abducted under circumstances mirroring
another daughter's death three years ago.
   The boy ``might be in jeopardy,'' police said.
   Robert and Paula Sims are the ``focus of the investigation'' in
the death of 6-week-old Heather Sims, whose reported disappearance
was similar to that of her sister in 1986.
   ``We feel very strong that we will eventually make an arrest in
this case,'' Sgt. Rick McCain said Friday.
   ``At this point in the investigation, we have found no evidence
of a kidnapping,'' he said.
   Sims, 37, was questioned for six hours Thursday night at Alton
police headquarters after an autopsy confirmed that an infant found
in a trash barrel in Missouri was Heather.
   Mrs. Sims was questioned for a few minutes, McCain said.
   The parents had never been ruled out as suspects, McCain said,
because of the similarities between Heather's disappearance and the
disappearance of their firstborn daughter, Loralei, in 1986.
   Their son was taken by the Illinois Department of Children and
Family Services, a decision ``based upon information that we
received last night that Randy Sims might be in jeopardy,'' he said.
   The case has dominated conversation in this town of 40,000,
across the Mississippi River from St. Louis.
   McCain said investigators have found no evidence to support the
Simses' claim that a masked gunman knocked out Mrs. Sims and
abducted the child late last Saturday _ a near duplication of their
report of Loralei's disappearance in 1986.
   No charges were filed in that case, which remains unsolved.
   A fisherman found Heather's body Wednesday night. It was wrapped
in a black plastic bag and placed in a trash barrel at a West
Alton, Mo., recreation area along the Mississippi River.
   The baby died of asphyxiation, McCain said. The autopsy revealed
she was killed about the time she was reported missing by her
parents.
   Police searched the couple's home Thursday and collected hair
and various fibers for laboratory analysis, McCain said.
   Black plastic bags _ similar to one in which the infant's body
was found _ were confiscated and sent to the FBI crime lab in
Washington.
   The couple told police that a masked gunman had approached Mrs.
Sims while she was taking out trash, forced her back into the home,
knocked her unconscious and took the infant. Sims said he was at
work at the time.
   In June 1986, the Simses, who then lived in nearby Brighton,
reported to authorities that an armed intruder barged into their
home while Sims was at work and took their 13-day-old firstborn.
   Remains believed to be Loralei's were discovered a week later
near the couple's home. No one was charged.
</TEXT>
