<FIRST>r a PM-BabyDeath     05-06 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Death,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Linares Family Couldn't Have Paid Medical Bills Anyway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who disconnected his comatose son from life
support equipment wasn't motivated by the mounting medical costs
because the family couldn't have paid the bills anyway, an attorney
said.
   ``The man is indigent,'' Kevin Smith said of his client, Rudolfo
Linares. ``The man doesn't have the means to pay anyway, so there
is no financial motivation at all in Mr. Linares' action.''
   The Chicago Tribune had reported Friday that Linares, who is
charged with murder, unhooked his 16-month-old son from the
breathing apparatus just four days before the state was set to cut
off medical benefits that had covered more than $100,000 in medical
costs for the child.
   Smith said a cutoff of public aid would not have significantly
increased the family's already overwhelming financial burden,
adding that the hospital had picked up about $500,000 worth of
bills that were uncovered by the state and which the family was
unable to pay.
   On April 26, Linares pulled out a gun in his son's hospital room
and kept hospital staff and police at bay while Samuel, died in his
arms. When the boy was dead, the tearful Linares handed over the
gun and the child's body.
   Linares, 23, is free on bond.
   In another development, Cook County medical examiner Robert
Stein ruled the manner of Samuel Linares' death ``undetermined,''
saying Friday he needs to research hospital records before making a
final decision.
   ``I've never come across a case where if the medical examiner
did not determine there was a homicide, you could come up with
murder,'' Smith said.
   On a section of the boy's death certificate, Stein declared the
immediate cause of Samuel's death to be a lack of oxygen to the
brain caused by the boy's choking on a balloon last summer.
   It was that Aug. 2, 1988, accident that sent the boy into the
irreversible coma.
</TEXT>
