<FIRST>r a PM-FamilyPoisoning     05-06 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Family Poisoning,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freedom Made Permanent for Man `Wrongfully Accused' in '67 Killings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARCADIA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special prosecutor made freedom permanent
for a man who served 21 years in the poisoning deaths of his
children, and the longtime inmate said he planned to celebrate in
the Gulf of Mexico.
   ``I want to take a swim and admire myself in the water,'' James
J. Richardson said in a telephone interview from Fort Walton Beach.
``I'll go deep down in the water. I will wade in it to be baptized
again and refresh my life.''
   Prosecutor Janet Reno said Friday that she found reasonable
doubt that Richardson killed his children and indicated he probably
was wrongfully accused. She said the state would not put him on
trial again.
   Richardson described the decision as ``splendid.''
   ``She's doing her job,'' he said. ``She's doing it like it
should be done. It should have been done 21 years ago.''
   The 53-year-old former orange picker was released from prison
April 25 after retired Circuit Judge Clifton Kelly accepted Ms.
Reno's recommendation that his 1968 trial was unfair.
   Ms. Reno, the Dade County state attorney appointed by Gov. Bob
Martinez as a special prosecutor, found evidence of substantial
trial errors and perjured testimony. Attorneys for Richardson
contended he was framed.
   ``It is apparent after a review of all evidence obtained in the
original investigation and the ensuing investigation that not only
could the state not prove that James Richardson was guilty beyond a
reasonable doubt (but) that James Richarson was probably wrongfully
accused,'' she wrote.
   She also faulted the murder investigation as ``totally
inadequate and incomplete.''
   ``Obvious leads were never pursued, critical questions were
never answered, glaring inconsistencies were never resolved,
standard investigative procedures were never followed,'' she said.
``The only evidence linking Richardson with the crime is the
testimony of three jailhouse inmates which we find totally
unreliable.''
   Frank Schaub, who prosecuted the case in 1968 and retired in
January, lashed out at Ms. Reno and said there is still strong
evidence against Richardson.
   ``How about prosecuting her for dropping the case?'' Schaub
said. ``She's incompetent to prosecute. It's ridiculous. I don't
think they ever convict anybody down there (in Miami). They have
the most lawless community in the world.''
   But Ms. Reno said it would be impossible to reopen the case
because evidence has been lost or destroyed and some witnesses have
died or become incapacitated.
   Richardson orginally was jailed on charges of poisoning all
seven of his children to collect $14,000 in life insurance. But he
stood trial in 1968 only for the slaying of his oldest
stepdaughter, 8-year-old Betty Jean.
   The children, ages 2 to 8, died after eating a meal of hog
jowls, rice, peas and grits tainted with the pesticide parathion
Oct. 25, 1967.
   Sworn affidavits have implicated the family's baby sitter, but
Kelly said the killer ``will quite likely never be known.''
   Ms. Reno said she was probing whether anyone involved in the
investigation could be charged with criminal misdeeds, but she
noted that the statute of limitations could hinder any prosecution.
   Richardson was sentenced to death after his conviction, but the
sentences was commuted to life in prison when the U.S. Supreme
Court struck down the death penalty in 1972.
   Richardson has entered a diet clinic run by former comedian Dick
Gregory in Fort Walton Beach. He said his celebration also would
include trips to Chicago and to the grocery store.
   ``I'm looking to get a pineapple upside-down cake. What I can't
eat I'm going to rub in my face,'' he said.
</TEXT>
