<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-06 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alfred Puglisi thought it strange to
receive a Christmas Card in May _ and stranger still that it was
from Christmas 1978.
   Puglisi received a Christmas card on Monday that was originally
mailed from Hallendale, Fla., in December 1978, according to the
earliest postmark.
   The envelope bore six different postmarks _ four from December
1978, one from January 1979 and one from last month. The postmarks
indicated the card made a few round trips between Florida and New
York during the past decade, Puglisi said.
   Post office officials in both Amsterdam and Hallendale said they
didn't know why the card lay dormant for so long.
   Puglisi said the card was from an old friend, Evelyn McCauley.
   ``I thought it was a birthday card, because (McCauley) knew when
my birthday was,'' Puglisi said. ``But ... I opened it and found
out it was a Christmas card with a note enclosed.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No one should go hungry at next weekend's
colossal cookout in this city along the Ohio River.
   Some 40,000 to 50,000 people are expected to attend the 11th
Annual International Barbecue Festival, where an estimated 40,000
pounds of mutton and 5,000 chickens will be barbecued over grills.
   The festival is listed among the ``Top 100 Events in North
America for 1989'' by the American Tour Bus Association. It begins
Friday and attracts barbecue lovers from across the country and
from Canada.
   An International Classic Cook-off Competition to be held at noon
Saturday is open to anyone who sets up to cook over a charcoal spit
or grill. But the weekend's competitions aren't just over recipes.
   A new event this year is the Little Miss and Mr. Mutton Contest,
open to children 4 to 6 years old. Organizers hope 20 to 30 couples
will enter the contest; the winners will receive trophies and serve
as official representatives of the festival.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANDUSKY, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even for veteran roller coaster riders
like John and Angela Biacofsky, the Magnum XL-200 wowed them like
no other.
   The ride at the Cedar Point amusement park is billed by its
promoters as the world's highest and faster roller coaster, a claim
several other amusement parks have used in recent years.
   The Biacofskys and about 150 other members of the American
Coaster Enthusiasts organization rode Magnum XL-200 on Friday for
their impressions.
   They called it the ride of their lives.
   ``It felt like you were dropping out of a parachute,'' Mrs.
Biacofsky of Willoughby said about the Magnum's first hill. ``You
went straight down. It's the most amazing roller coaster I've ever
been on. You just can't believe it.''
   ``Awesome,'' said Biacofsky.
   The coaster's speed on its first, 201-foot-high hill is 70 to 75
mph. It includes 5,106 feet of track and three tunnels with smoke
machines.
   The public can test it today, as the park opens for the season.
</TEXT>
