<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--HouseSnake     05-06 0153</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--House Snake,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Home Ransacked by Snake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 4{-foot kingsnake managed to get into
a house and made such a mess that the house's owner thought a
burglar had ransacked the property, officials said.
   The snake on Thursday knocked over tables and other furniture in
the den while seeking an escape route. When the owner returned to
his home, he thought he had been robbed ``until he found a snake
track leading to the fireplace,'' said Animal Control Officer Diana
Marcantel.
   Marcantel and another officer captured the reptile under a sofa
following a 10-minute, furniture-moving scramble. The non-poisonous
snake was released in an uninhabited area.
   The homeowner, who was not identified, noticed the snake sunning
on his roof earlier in the week. Kingsnakes don't like water, and
recent rains may have caused it to seek refuge in the attic before
it got into the den, Marcantel said.
</TEXT>
