<FIRST>r i PM-India-Gas     05-06 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Gas,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>207 Hospitalized from Chlorine Gas Leak</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chlorine gas that leaked from a
fertilizer company's tanker truck enveloped parts of a densely
populated suburb and nearby bus station, injuring more than 200
people, police said today.
   The gas spewed Friday night for two hours from one of five
chlorine drums carried by the tanker, said a police official who
cannot be identified under briefing rules.
   The driver and his companion, apparently overwhelmed by the
fumes, abandoned the tanker near a bus station, The Times of London
newspaper said. Most of the victims were waiting passengers, the
English-language newspaper said today.
   Police said 207 people were admitted to six hospitals, and that
151 of them were discharged today.
   Many of the victims, who reported irritation in the eyes, nose
and throat, had fainted but were ``out of danger now,'' said M.P.
Khare, a physician who heads a government hospital where 77 people
were admitted.
   The Times of India newspaper quoted the engineers of the company
_ Shriram Foods and Fertilizers Industries _ as saying the leak was
caused by a faulty safety valve of the one-ton-capacity drum.
   Officials of the company were not available for comment.
</TEXT>
