<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Ethiopia     05-06 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Ethiopia,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emperor Selassie's Son Announces Ascension to Throne</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   His throne was a simple chair, his robes a blue
suit and his palace a London apartment.
   Fourteen years after his father's death, Haile Selassie's exiled
73-year-old son announced at a news conference Friday his ascension
to the Imperial Throne of Ethiopia, where a Marxist-led government
now rules.
   Seated beside his white-robed empress and surrounded by
family-in-exile, Ahma Selassie I of Ethiopia, the Conquering Lion
of the Tribe of Judah, indicated they believe the government will
not last long and that he will return to reign as a constitutional
monarch and bring democracy to the nation.
   Ahma Selassie's government-in-exile, however, has not been
recognized by foreign states, only by about 100 Ethiopian state
kings.
   The East African nation of 43 million inhabitants is one of the
world's poorest countries. It is torn by civil war and periodically
swept by famine.
   Haile Selassie became emperor in 1930. He pleaded unsuccessfully
to the now defunct League of Nations against the 1935-36 conquest
of his country by Italy. He was in England until his rule was
restored in 1941.
   He ruled Ethiopia for a total of 44 years as head of one of the
world's last feudal states. But on Sept. 12, 1974, he was deposed
by a military clique that established a Marxist government led by
Lt. Col. Mengistu Haile Mariam and backed by the Soviet Union.
   Haile Selassie, who had made Ethiopia the United States'
strongest ally in Africa, was last seen alive climbing into the
back seat of a car outside his main palace in the capital Addis
Ababa.
   He died 11 months later in detention under obscure circumstances
at age 83.
   At the time his father was deposed, the younger Selassie had
been living in London for two years undergoing treatment for
diabetes.
   Seife Michael Zewde, son-in-law of Ahma Selassie and Privy
Councilor to the throne, said 3 million Ethiopians are in exile,
the army has suffered defections ``en masse'' and Mengistu's
government is spending nearly 80 percent of its budget on the
military.
   Asked when Ahma Selassie might return, Empress Medferiash Work
said: ``Since the Ethiopian people are fed up to the teeth with
being oppressed and murdered at random, then the will of God should
be the decider _ soon.''
   Zewde said Ahma Selassie was asked to take the throne by about
100 Ethiopian state kings and 62 locally elected officials.
   The emperor has refused to hold any coronation outside Ethopian
soil, so he has postponed it until he gains power, said Zewde, who
acted as translator.
   The ``United Ethiopian Patriots Solidarity Armed Forces,'' or
military arm of the locally elected council, is fighting the
government, Zewde said. ``In all the countryside they are dying by
the hundreds,'' he said.
   Other rebel groups fighting the Marxist government for
independence in Eritrea and Tigre provinces have been in existence
since before Selassie's ouster.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890506-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0604EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bolivia-Elections     05-06 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bolivia-Elections,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poor Bolivia on Edge on Eve of Presidential Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police guarded polling places and
helicopters delivered ballots to remote mountain and jungle areas
as Bolivians prepared to vote for president Sunday.
   No violence was reported as the electoral court late Friday
completed the nationwide distribution of ballots.
   More than 2 million Bolivians are expected to cast their votes
for 10 parties with candidates ranging from a former dictator to a
farming leader who was shot and crippled by another ex-dictator.
   Most polls place former dictator Gen. Hugo Banzer Suarez of the
rightist Nationalist Democratic Action as the front runner, with
Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada of the conservative Revolutionary
Nationalist Movement competing for second with the Social
Democratic Movement of the Revolutionary Left.
   President Victor Paz Estenssoro, 81, is retiring from politics.
   For a country once considered one of the most unstable in South
America, August will mark the seventh year of democratic rule. It
will also be the first transfer of power to a new government in 25
years by a president who has completed his term.
   Policeman were deployed Friday to schools throughout the country
where electoral boxes and ballots were distributed by electoral
officials. The distribution was handled without major delays,
including the use of helicopters to remote indian communities in
the Andean highlands and tropical lowlands.
   Political campaigning came to an end midnight Thursday and the
three leading candidates said that were confident they would win a
majority of votes Sunday.
   At the closing of his campaign Thursday, Banzer assured a large
crowd gathered in the semitropical city of Santa Cruz, 470 miles
east of La Paz, his victory with the support of ``men and woman who
desire economic stability that will assure their and their
children's future.''
   Banzer, 62, seized power in a 1971 coup that toppled a leftist
military dictatorship and ruled until 1978, when popular pressure
forced him to call elections. The Bolivian Rights Assembly says
during Banzer's government there were 72 deaths, 78 disappearences,
14,537 illegal detentions and 3,000 exiles.
   Sanchez Lozada, 58, a University of Chicago philosophy graduate,
promised to create 250,000 new jobs and 150,000 new dwellings. He
was planning minister under Estenssoro and one of the architects of
a stabilization program that lowered inflation from 24,000 percent
four years ago to 2 percent for the first quarter of this year.
   However, Bolivia's economy remains plagued by high unemployment
and continued low prices on tin, their primary export.
   For a candidate to win the presidency he must receive more than
50 percent of the votes. Since none of the candidates is expected
to receive more than 30 percent, the congress elected Sunday will
convene Aug. 4 to elect Bolivia's 77th president.
   The campaign began early this year and cost at least $10
million, a record for a country of 6 million where the minimum
monthly wage is $45.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890506-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0622EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spearfishing     05-06 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spearfishing,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mass Arrests Made At Spearfishing Protest On Eve Of Regular Fishing
Season</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD EGGLESTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOULDER JUNCTION, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 people were arrested
in the biggest protest yet over an Indian tribe's right to
spearfish in off-reservation water.
   Police estimated about 850 people gathered at Trout Lake as six
boatloads of spearers from the Lac du Flambeau Chippewa reservation
set out on a cold, snowy Friday evening.
   The crowd included about 100 to 150 supporters of the Indians,
police estimated. More than 150 officers were stationed at the boat
landing.
   Federal courts have ruled that tribal members retain the right
to spear walleyed pike and other game fish with spotlights during
spring spawning season, much as their forefathers did by torchlight.
   Spearfishing has generated emotional protests from non-Chippewa
who contend the treaty-reserved rights are discriminatory and
threaten fish populations. Protesters waving American flags and
chanting ``equal rights'' surged across a police line and sat down
at the boat landing. More than 105 were arrested by early today,
and they were hauled away in vans and a school bus.
   The protest began hours after U.S. District Judge Barbara Crabb
refused to grant a state request to halt the spearing before sport
anglers open their season today.
   Tribal members have faced crowds of hundreds of protesters, some
shouting racial slurs and throwing rocks, since the spearing season
began April 23. There had been more than 100 arrests before Friday.
   This is the fifth year Wisconsin's six Chippewa bands have
speared walleye from northern Wisconsin lakes since a federal court
ruled the tribe retained the rights to hunt, fish and gather wild
grain under 19th century treaties that ceded land to the United
States.
   Tensions over the spring spearfishing have increased each year.
They have heightened this year after the state reduced the
sportfishing walleye catch limit on the 254 lakes the tribe has
targeted for spearing.
</TEXT>
