<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Kidnap     05-06 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0635</SECOND>
<HEAD>Security Sources Have No New Leads on Abducted Relief Worker</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security sources in southern Lebanon said
today they had no new leads on the whereabouts of a West German
relief worker who was abducted two days ago.
   ``The whole case of Markus Michael is a mystery,'' said a source
at the Nasserite Sunni Moslem militia, which is in charge of
security in Sidon.
   There has been no claim of responsibility in Thursday's
incident, which is believed linked to the trial of a Lebanese
hijacker in Frankfurt, West Germany.
   The 25-year-old was kidnapped by five unidentified gunmen on
Sidon's southern edge along with two fellow relief workers from the
ASME-Humanitas agency, Heinrich Struebig and Petra Schnitzler.
   Struebig, 48, and Schnitzler, 26, were released Friday. They met
the Nasserite militia's leader Mustafa Saad in Sidon for 10
minutes, but refused to talk to the press. Struebig is an
administrator and Schnitzler a nurse.
   ``The released two haven't donated any significant information
about the captors or their motives,'' the source said. He refused
to be named.
   ``They only said they wanted to talk to their headquarters in
Germany and to their government. It seems they wanted to relay some
information to Germany,'' the source added.
   The West German Embassy refused comment on the case.
   In Bonn, West German Foreign Ministry spokesman Hans Schumacher
noted that Struebig and Schnitzler had disappeared for two days in
Lebanon under similar circumstances a year ago.
   He said he considered the latest 10-hour disappearance ``a bit
strange.''
   The three worked from a base between the Palestinian refugee
camps of Ein el-Hilweh and Mieh Mieh on Sidon's eastern edge. The
Sidon region, 25 miles south of Beirut, is a PLO stronghold.
   Lt. Col. Wajih Abu Ali, commander of the PLO's military police
in the Sidon region and in charge of protecting the ASME-Humanitas
base, also said the two who were released have refused to cooperate
with investigators.
   ``They refused to give us any information about the kidnappers,
their demands, if any, and the place where they were held,'' Abu
Ali told reporters in Mieh Mieh. ``They only said they were
threatened.''
   On Friday, Abu Ali said Struebig and Schnitzler told him the
kidnappers have threatened to kill Michael if they divulged any
information about the abduction.
   The daily newspaper Al-Liwaa, which publishes in Moslem west
Beirut, said the captors wanted a ``lenient sentence'' for Mohammed
Ali Hamadi, a Lebanese Shiite Moslem terrorist held in Frankfurt.
It cited no source for the report.
   West German prosecutors have demanded a life sentence for Hamadi
for involvement in the 1985 hijacking of a TWA jetliner in which a
U.S. Navy diver was shot to death and his body tossed onto the
airport tarmac, two U.S. men were severely beaten and 37 other
passengers were held hostage 17 days.
   Abu Ali refused comment on the newspaper report, but a deputy
said Friday the two released told him the kidnapping was linked to
Hamadi.
   The source at the Nasserite militia said: ``I find it strange.
If the kidnappers want to pressure the Germans, then why did they
release two German hostages?''
   A verdict in Hamadi's case is expected within two weeks.
   Hamadi's elder brother, Abdul-Hadi, heads the security apparatus
for the Iranian-backed extremist group Hezbollah, or Party of God,
which is the umbrella organization for underground pro-Iranian
factions holding Western captives.
   In addition to Michael, there are 15 foreigners held in Lebanon
_ nine Americans, three Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and a
Belgian.
   The hostage held longest is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
