<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-06 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms Follow Tornadoes; Record Cold In Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Severe thunderstorms today followed killer tornadoes over
portions of the Carolinas, dumping more than an inch of rain in an
hour, and flood watches were posted in the middle and northern
Atlantic coastal states.
   More than two dozen tornadoes touched down Friday evening in the
Carolinas. The hardest-hit area appeared to be in Spartanburg
County, S.C., where a tornado killed at least three people and
injured more than 30.
   In all, the storm was blamed for the deaths of at least 16
people since Thursday night. Four people died in North Carolina;
three in South Carolina; one in Louisiana; seven in Texas; and one
in Oklahoma.
   Thunderstorms produced baseball-sized hail and 60 mph winds in
Lexington County, S.C., where numerous trees and power lines were
reported down.
   Trailers were overturned in Farmington, N.C., and trees fell
onto mobile homes in Summerfield and Rockingham counties.
   A severe thunderstorm struck Baltimore, uprooting trees with
wind gusts to 78 mph.
   Richmond, Va., received more than an inch of rain in one hour
early this morning, while some central Virginia and western
Maryland towns reported up to 5 inches of rain from the storm.
   Parts of eastern Pennsylvania received 2 to 4 inches of rain. Up
to 2 inches fell in the Washington, D.C., area in the six hours
ending at 2 a.m. EDT.
   Rain and scattered thunderstorms spread northeast into nearly
all of New York and New England by early this morning. With the
ground saturated from recent rainfall, flooding was possible in
portions of the middle and northern Atlantic coastal states, from
Virginia to southern Maine.
   Light snow fell across much of Minnesota, Wisconsin and northern
Michigan early today.
   Unseasonable cold settled into the upper Mississippi Valley and
the northern and central Plains, setting records Friday for the
date in Minneapolis, with 26 degrees, and Rochester, Minn., also 26.
   The high for the nation Saturday was 107 degrees in Laughlin,
Nev., Bullhead City, Ariz., and Buckeye, Ariz.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from North
Carolina across the mid-Atlantic states to southern New England;
scattered showers and thunderstorms extending from Florida across
southeast Georgia to eastern South Carolina; rain across Maine and
New Hampshire; scattered rain from the lower Great Lakes to the
Ohio and Tennessee valleys; rain and snow showers scattered over
the upper Great Lakes; and sunny skies from the Plains to the
Plateau.
   Highs were to be in the 40s from eastern sections of Minnesota
and Iowa to much of the Great Lakes, with readings in the upper 30s
over Upper Michigan; in the 50s and 60s from the northern and
middle Atlantic coast states across the Ohio, Tennessee and middle
Mississippi valleys to the northern and central Plains; in the 90s
from the interior valleys of California across southern sections of
Arizona and New Mexico to far west Texas; and from 100 to 110 over
the desert Southwest. Elsewhere, highs mostly were to be in the 70s
and 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 20
degrees in Duluth, Minn., to 87 degrees in Phoenix and Glendale,
Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 62 fair; Boston 50 rain; Buffalo 51 showers;
Charleston, S.C., 68 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 42 fair; Cleveland
48 fair; Detroit 42 partly cloudy; Miami 76 fair; New York 58 rain;
Philadelphia 64 showers; Pittsburgh 50 drizzle; Portland, Maine, 47
rain; Washington 58 rain.
   _Central: Bismarck 29 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 62 fair; Denver 47
fair; Des Moines 32 fair; Indianapolis 45 partly cloudy; Kansas
City 38 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 26 windy; Nashville 50 foggy;
New Orleans 65 fair; St. Louis 46 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 63 fair; Anchorage 37 cloudy; Las Vegas 80
partly cloudy; Los Angeles 63 hazy; Phoenix 87 cloudy; Salt Lake
City 56 fair; San Diego 62 fair; San Francisco 61 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 50 rain; Toronto 46 cloudy.
</TEXT>
