<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Defection     05-06 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Defection,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two North Korean Defectors Say Olympics Showed Them Real Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two North Korean students who defected
in Poland said upon arrival today that only after viewing the Seoul
Olympics on television did they see they had been lied to by their
Communist government.
   ``We were taught to believe that North Korea is the best country
in the world to live in, but once in the outside world, we realized
that we had been deceived,'' said Kim Un Hwak at an airport news
conference.
   Kim and Dong Young Hoon, both 24, said they were surprised when
they saw television footage in Poland showing a developed South
Korea during last year's Summer Olympics.
   ``In North Korea, we had been taught to believe that South Korea
is shambles and a very poor country, but it was a lie,'' Dong said.
   Kim and Dong, who defected to the West late last month through a
European country, were escorted to South Korea by government
officials.
   The two said they were sorry for their families in North Korea,
but they were happy to be in South Korea, which they believe is
also ``part of our homeland.''
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Chang Hoon said Dong had been
studying at Gdansk University and Kim at Warsaw Engineering College
when they sought political asylum at a South Korean embassy in a
Western European nation.
   Under an international convention, the South Korean embassy had
no power to grant asylum to the North Koreans, so authorities of
the European nation were asked to intervene, he said.
   The European nation involved asked not to be identified for now,
Hoon added.
   It was the second time this year that North Korean students in
East Europe had defected to South Korea through west Europe.
   On Feb. 9, two North Korean students _ Cho Sung Gun, 22, and Kim
Un Chul, 22 _ who had been studying in Czechoslovakia, defected to
South Korea.
   The Korean peninsula was divided into communist North Korea and
capitalist South Korea in 1945 at the end of World War II. The two
Koreas fought a bloody war from 1950-53.
</TEXT>
