<FIRST>r i PM-Iraq-Crash     05-06 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iraq-Crash,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iraqi's No. 2 Military Chief Dies in Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adnan Khairallah, the deputy commander in
chief of the armed forces and defense minister, was killed in a
helicopter crash during a sandstorm in northern Iraq, President
Saddam Hussein said today.
   Hussein said in a statement broadcast over state radio that the
50-year-old general, considered the second most powerful man after
Hussein in the tight-knit clan that rules Iraq, died Friday.
   Khairallah was both a cousin and brother-in-law to the Iraqi
leader.
   Khairallah was appointed defense minister in 1979, days after
Hussein assumed the presidency, and held the post throughout the
8-year Iran-Iraq conflict that ended in a cease-fire in August.
   The president described him as ``one of the distingushed war
heros and a sparkling star in Iraq's sky.''
   Hussein said Khairallah died instantly when the helicopter went
down en route to Baghdad from the northern mountain resort of
Sarsang near Mosul, which lies 280 miles northwest of Baghdad.
   He said everyone on board perished except for one person, but he
did not elaborate. The statement said two escorting helicopters
survived ``the crazy storm.'' The site of the crash was not
reported.
   The helicopter was believed to be one of the U.S.-manufactured
Bell helicopters used to whisk leaders around the country.
   The radio said Khairallah would be given a state funeral today
in Baghdad and buried in the city of Tikrit, the clan seat 115
miles north of the capital.
   Saddam said Khairallah was in the northern Kurdish region
inspecting army positions when he joined the president's family who
were touring the same area.
   The government has instituted a huge relocation program for the
rebellious minority, razing thousands of dwellings. The U.S. Senate
and a several Western human rights organizations have protested the
army assault on Kurdish areas last summer, accusing Iraq of using
poison gas. Iraq denied the charges.
   Khairallah was a member of the ruling Revolutionary Command
Council and the highest command of the Baath Party.
   Khairallah took part in the bloodless coup that toppled
President Abdul Rahaman Aref and brought the ruling Baath party to
power in 1968.
   Khairallah was married to the daughter of ex-president Ahmed
Hassan Al-Bakr, who resigned in 1979. He has three children.
</TEXT>
