<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--MassGrave     05-06 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Mass Grave,0152</SECOND>
<HEAD>Developers Unearth Cemetery Where 38,000 May Be Buried</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developers have unearthed portions of an old
cemetery that an amateur historian says could contain the remains
of 38,000 people, including victims of the 1871 Chicago fire.
   The 20-acre site was once the location of the Cook County poor
house and a state mental hospital, said Barry Fleig, who is writing
a guidebook to Chicago cemeteries.
   Fleig said he can document the burial of 17,000 bodies there
from 1851 through 1912, and said the site could contain the remains
of as many as 38,000 people.
   Developers of a housing complex unearthed the site and must have
the bones reburied before building can continue, a city health
official ruled Friday.
   ``There's no specific health or disease problem at this point;
it's basically just respect for the dead,'' said Roger Cieslik, a
health department supervisory.
</TEXT>
