<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Crash     05-06 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Crash,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tourist Plane Crashes in Jungle Near Cancun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commercial plane carrying up to 17 U.S.
tourists crashed in the jungles of Yucatan Peninsula after an
engine failed but officials said no one was killed.
   Diego Acosta, commander of the Red Cross in Cancun, said army
troops in radio contact with the pilot of the Aerocozumel flight
early today said there were injuries. He said he had no details on
the seriousness of the injuries.
   The three-engine, British-made Trislander, flying from the
archeological site of Chichen Itza to the island resort of Cozumel
crashed about two miles outside the Playa del Carmen airport, 25
miles south of Cancun.
   The Excelsior news agency said the aircraft, which was filled to
capacity and had one pilot, was able to land despite having lost
power in one of its engines. It said all passengers were believed
to be American.
   ``The problem is that the people (passengers) have not come out
because it is impossible because of the number of trees. From the
edge of the road it's about three miles to where the plane is,''
Acosta said.
   While the jungle terrain hampered rescue operations, authorities
managed to air-drop food and medicine.
   Cmdr. Agustin Ortega Martin del Campo, army commander for the
region about 900 miles east of Mexico City, said a helicopter had
circled the site but was unable to land because of the jungle
growth.
   Speaking by telephone from Cancun, he said about 30 Mexican
soldiers were going overland to the site but were slowed by the
jungle terrain and lack of nearby roads.
</TEXT>
