<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0801EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India     05-06 0235</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sikh Separatists Storm Bank, Kill Two in Gunfire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARUN JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMMU, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh separatists stormed into a bank in this
northern city today and sprayed the lobby with gunfire, killing two
customers and seriously wounding two employees, police said.
   ``They never wanted to loot the bank, they just wanted to
kill,'' said Kapoor Singh, a Sikh bank employee who was
hospitalized after sustaining bullet injuries in the shoulder and
back during the attack.
   Four young turbaned Sikhs came on two motorscooters and barged
into the government-owned bank minutes after it opened, said Police
Chief Shoeb Ali.
   After the shooting, which lasted about two minutes, the
attackers fled on their scooters, Ali said.
   He said the attackers were anti-government Sikh extremists who
are fighting to set up a Sikh nation in the neighboring state of
Punjab. Jammu, the capital of Jammu and Kashmir state, is 45 miles
north of the Punjab border.
   Sikh militants have killed at least 630 people this year in
Punjab, a rich farming state, in their quest for the separate
homeland.
   Separatists among the Sikh community, which forms 2 percent of
India's 880 million population, say they are discriminated by the
Hindu majority.
   The 7-year-old separatist campaign has been largely confined to
Punjab, but the extremists have sometimes attacked and killed
people in Haryana, Jammu and Kashmir and Rajasthan states that
surround Punjab.
</TEXT>
