<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0839EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China 2ndLd-Writethru   05-06 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0468,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beijing University Students Vow To Continue Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 14 grafs to UPDATE with students to continue boycott,
details of statement from new student group. Pickup 16th pvs, ``Zhao's
statements...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beijing University students, the last holdouts in
a two-week boycott of classes, voted today to continue their strike
and press the government for democratic reforms.
   Student activists at the university, China's most prestigious,
said they would try to rekindle the boycott at other schools, where
classes began returning to normal Friday.
   Meanwhile, a newly formed student group representing at least 24
universities sent an appeal today to the government for talks on
democratic reform and an end to corruption.
   The two-page appeal was sent two days after Communist Party
chief Zhao Ziyang made a conciliatory call for talks.
   The statement called for ``sincere, construction and open
talks'' and ``requested'' they be open to the media. The students
said they would return to government offices Monday to hear the
response of the leadership, which has insisted talks must be
conducted through officially established student unions.
   The new group, called the Student Dialogue Representative group,
was formed after the government refused to meet with the
independent student union that has organized three weeks of
protests, including several mass demonstrations.
   The protests have been the largest in 40 years of communist rule.
   Shen Tong, general secretary of the new group, said its goals
were the same as the United Association of Beijing Universities, an
umbrella group linking independent student unions on more than 40
city campuses.
   The new group includes representatives from Beijing University,
where students overwhelmingly voted to continue a class boycott
that began April 24.
   ``If we persist a while longer, some of our demands will be
realized. If we don't, all of our efforts will be wasted,'' one
Beijing University student shouted through a loudspeaker as several
hundred classmates gathered on campus.
   Each dormitory room, which sleep six to eight people, received a
vote, and the final tally was 865 rooms to 303 in favor of the
boycott, with more than 100 rooms abstaining, student leaders said.
The vote in support of the independent union, which conducted the
election, was 871-153 rooms.
   Some students were angry over reports of authorities at one
school threatening activists with expulsion and of tactics by
officials at the Beijing College of Aeronautics.
   Officials there cut off electricity on campus for four days in
an effort to discourage the students from joining protests, peeled
off student protest posters and locked the campus gates so students
could not take part in Thursday's march.
   Zhao and Premier Li Peng indicated after the march that the
government planned talks with the students. They gave no specifics,
however.
   Zhao's statements on the student movement were the most
conciliatory yet by any government leader and included an
acknowledgement that the protesters were correct in demanding
``that we fix maladies in our work.''
   But one Beijing University activist dismissed Zhao's speech as
lacking ``substantial content.'' ``It's just talk,'' he said.
   The state press today hailed the return to classes of most of
the students. But several acknowleged that students were not
satisfied with Zhao's speech and believed he underestimated the
extent of corruption.
   A railway worker who took part in violence triggered by an April
22 student march in Xian was convicted of arson and theft and
sentenced to death, the Legal Daily reported. Zhang Jun was on
trial with more than 900 other people accused of attacking
government offices in the northwestern tourist city after a student
march.
   The report said Zhang set several vehicles on fire, stole small
items from inside them and threw rocks and bricks through
government office windows and at police. About 130 security forces
were injured in the violence, but no deaths were reported.
</TEXT>
