<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     05-06 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shelling Continues In Lebanon As Cease-Fire Monitors Deployed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem forces shelled the coast of the
Christian heartland north of Beirut today as the Arab League
struggled to deploy an observer force to monitor a widely ignored
truce.
   Police said artillery and rocket salvos fired sporadically from
Syrian-controlled west Beirut landed at the shoreline between the
ports of Jounieh and Byblos. Christian army units did not return
fire.
   No casualties were reported. At least 278 people have been
killed and 1,010 wounded since the current round in Lebanon's
14-year-old civil war began March 8, pitting Christians against an
alliance of Syrian and Druse forces.
   A police spokesman said the shelling kept the only escape routes
closed for the 1 million Christians in the 310-square-mile
Christian enclave.
   Two Cypriot-flagged ferry boats that occasionally have been
running the gantlet of Syrian fire to transport Christians from
Jounieh and Byblos to Larnaca, Cyprus, suspended their shuttles
again Thursday.
   Druse and leftist Moslems allied with Syria have declared they
will stop the coastal shelling only when the observer force from
six Arab nations is in place along Beirut's dividing Green Line and
neighboring hills.
   They also have demanded that Arab observers be stationed in
Jounieh and Byblos to determine whether new supplies of Iraqi arms
are received by the mainly Christian troops of the army commander,
Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Iraq, Syria's main Arab foe, expressed support for Aoun when he
declared in March his ``war of liberation'' against Syria, which
maintains 40,000 troops in Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate.
   Aoun, who has agreed to lift his military blockade of illegal
harbors run by Moslem militias south of Beirut, has denied
receiving any arms from Iraq.
   The blockade Aoun began March 6 ignited the current fighting.
Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party militia
retaliated by shelling the Christian enclave. The Syrians later
joined the shelling and closed the enclave's land exits.
   The Lebanese media said the Kuwaiti commander of the 321-man
observer force, Brig. Gen. Ali Momen, was due in Damascus on Sunday
for talks with Syrian government leaders before coming to Beirut to
take up his post.
   Contingents of the force contributed by Kuwait, Tunisia,
Algeria, Jordan, Sudan and North Yemen are expected to be airlifted
to Beirut late next week, according to media reports.
   The Arab League's Council of Foreign Ministers decided to form
the force last month in a bid to halt the current fighting.
   The council also called a cease-fire April 28. But it had since
been violated daily by sporadic shelling of the Christian enclave's
coast.
</TEXT>
