<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1012EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Politics     05-06 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Politics,0356</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cardenas Marks Birth of New Leftist Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Mexicans converged on
Mexico City's Zocalo plaza to mark the birth of a new leftist
political party headed by Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, runner-up in July's
presidential election.
   ``The existence of the Revolutionary Democratic Party gives the
people a real alternative _ that of democratic change,'' he told
the crowd Friday.
   Cardenas, candidate of the National Democratic Front coalition,
finished second in the July 6 presidential vote to Carlos Salinas
de Gortari of the Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has
governed Mexico for 60 years.
   Supporters of Cardenas allege widespread fraud gave the victory
to Salinas, whose 50 percent total was the lowest ever for a
governing party candidate.
   Cardenas said the new political party would ``fight for the
restoration of national sovereignty, the rule of law and eradicate
corruption.'' He called for a suspension of payments on Mexico's
$107 billion foreign debt that, he said, ``leave Mexicans with
hunger salaries.''
   ``The real debt is with the Mexican people,'' Cardenas declared,
calling for wage increases for workers and higher guaranteed prices
for peasant crops.
   The leftist leader also said the new party would advocate an
expansion of Mexico's relations with other Latin American countries
and stress economic development independent of the United States.
   ``Mexico must never join multinational organizations with the
United States, as has been the case under the silent integration
policy of the government since 1982,'' he declared. That year
generally is considered the start of Mexico's foreign trade
liberalization, applauded by U.S. leaders.
   Cardenas also vowed to fight for fraud-free local and national
elections.
   ``Even if in July we were defrauded of victory ... we will
continue to work constitutionally to achieve our goals,'' he
declared.
   Cardenas said the new party obtained enough signatures during a
voter registration drive to file with the government for formal
political party status. To register a political party Mexican law
requires 65,000 signatures plus at least 100 signatures in each of
the country's 300 election districts.
</TEXT>
