<FIRST>r i PM-NewCaledonia     05-06 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-New Caledonia,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged in Attack on New Caledonia Independence Leaders</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A magistrate today filed murder
charges against a hard-line separatist in the slaying of two senior
leaders of the independence movement in this French Pacific
territory.
   Andre Tangopi was charged in the shooting deaths of Jean-Marie
Tjibaou, leader of the Kanak Socialist National Liberation Front,
and his top assistant, Yeiwene Yeiwene. Police did not say what
role Tangopi played in the attack.
   He was wounded in an exchange of gunfire that followed the
assassination and was under police guard in the hospital at Noumea,
the provincial capital.
   The two leaders were shot and killed Thursday by Djubelly Wea,
who, like Tangopi, opposed Tjibaou's moderate policies. Wea was
killed by Tjibaou's bodyguards after the attack, which occurred on
the island of Ouvea.
   Police today released two other suspects in the killings: Paoula
Wea, a nephew of Wea, and Fessen Tuet, a statement from the
prosecutors office said.
   Elections planned for June 11 were postponed after the killings,
and they have not been rescheduled, French Premier Michel Rocard
has said. Rocard was to attend Tjibaou's funeral on Sunday.
   The senior surviving leader of the front, Leopold Joredie, said
the group would continue participating in a ``peace process'' that
began last year and is to culminate in a 1998 referendum on
independence.
   A witness has said five or six gunmen participated in the
assassination.
   Tjibaou and Yeiwene were in Ouvea to take part in ceremonies
marking the first anniversary of the May 5 assault by French
military police on a cave where separatists were holding more than
20 police hostage. In the fighting, 19 separatists and two French
policemen died.
   The ceremonies were called off after Thursday's attack.
   Native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, make up 43 percent of the
inhabitants of New Caledonia, which are islands 1,000 miles east of
Australia. Most natives favor independence.
   European settlers and their descendants make up 37 percent,
nearly all of whom want to remain part of France. The remaining
Polynesians and Asians, also are favorable to retaining the link to
France.
</TEXT>
