<DOCNO> AP890506-0066 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1047EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-SpaceShuttle 3rdLd-Writethru a0485 05-06 0902</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0485,0923</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magellan Zips Deeper Into Space, Atlantis Astronauts Experiments</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4-6th grafs, bgng, `The songs...', with 6 grafs to CORRECT
name of `wild blue yonder' song to `The Air Force Song,' and to UPDATE
with minor trouble during breakfast. Picks up 7th graf, `Earlier today...'.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPACE CENTER, Houston (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Astronauts awakened to their alma
maters' school songs today and resumed a light work schedule, while
the robot Magellan probe they had launched earlier raced onward at
7,000 mph on its 15-month voyage to Venus.
   The five astronauts aboard the shuttle Atlantis began work on
routine tests aboard the orbiter, including one that calls for
photographing night lightning strikes in the clouds below.
   Their day began shortly before 8 a.m. CDT with a medley of
military and schools tunes played for them by Mission Control.
   ``Good morning, Houston. Thanks for the great music,'' Atlantis
commander David Walker said. ``We did sleep well and we're ready to
roll today.''
   The songs played were ``Anchors Aweigh,'' for Walker, a Navy
captain; ``The Air Force Song'' (``Off we go, into the wild blue
yonder...'') for pilot Ronald Grabe and mission specialist Mark
Lee, both Air Force Academy graduates; and the school songs for
Colorado State, mission specialist Mary Cleave's alma mater, and
Florida State, which mission specialist Norman Thagard's attended.
   Except for a minor difficulty during breakfast, Atlantis
remained in good shape as the astronauts began their second full
day in orbit.
   ``All systems on Atlantis (are) functioning very well,'' Mission
Control commentator Jeffrey Carr said. ``We're starting the day
with a very clean bird, a very clean slate.''
   The astronauts had a little difficulty with breakfast when a
galley water device malfunctioned, dispensing ``almost any amount''
of water it wanted despite a precise setting, Lee said.
   ``It must be poetic justice to have a galley mal (malfunction)
with a maggot on board,'' Walker joked. Members of Lee's astronaut
class named themselves ``maggots.''
   After some unsuccessful tinkering with the device, the
astronauts attached a hose to it so they could control the flow of
water. Some of the freeze-dried food packages need a dose of hot or
cold water.
   Earlier today, while the crew members slept, cargo bay cameras
provided spectacular views of the Middle East and Africa. The
cameras were maneuvered by a ground controller and could be seen on
NASA television.
   The Magellan planetary probe, which will travel 806 million
miles before reaching Venus, was on a near perfect path and was in
excellent condition, officials said.
   It was only half a degree off normal, but that deviation was
expected and will be adjusted May 21 when a ground station sends a
signal to trigger a small motor firing on the probe, they said.
   Magellan, gently ejected Thursday night from the shuttle's cargo
bay, began its journey at a rate of 25,000 mph but had slowed
gradually to a cruising speed of about 7,000 mph. This morning, it
was expected to pass the plane of the moon some 240,000 miles from
Earth.
   When it reaches Venus in August 1990, the tug of the planet's
gravity will have increased the speed again to about 25,000 mph.
Once in orbit, the probe will use its high resolution radar system
to map up to 90 percent of the Venusian surface.
   Those images, enhanced by computers, are expected to show
features as small as a football field and be 10 times clearer than
pictures obtained by earlier spacecraft. The pictures should
provide an avalanche of data that could help scientists discover
how Venus evolved so differently from Earth.
   The $550 million mission is the first U.S. planetary project in
11 years and the first to be deployed from a shuttle.
   The astronauts' workload has been light because the heavy weight
of Magellan and its rocket booster, totaling 45,000 pounds,
restricted the number of experiments they could carry on the
four-day mission. The probe weighs 7,600 pounds.
   The crew members methodically went about their work Friday,
talking only sparingly with ground controllers at the Johnson Space
Center.
   Walker took some time out to thank the tracking station crews at
Guam and Santiago, Chile, who are covering their last shuttle
mission.
   The stations are among several being phased out because of the
completion of a network of communications satellites that allows
ground controllers to have nearly constant contact with shuttle
astronauts.
   ``Thanks for all the good work,'' Walker told the Santiago crew
late Friday night.
   Earlier Friday, the astronauts worked with a 128-pound
metals-processing furnace the size of a small microwave oven.
Samples of indium and selenium were melted and resolidified in the
furnace to see how they react in weightlessness.
   Potential applications for such space-made materials include
advanced electronic and optical devices.
   Also on board are medical experiments and several cameras for
photographing the Earth and lightning systems. Photographs of such
lightning strikes may one day help scientists improve weather
forecasting methods.
   Flight Director Ron Dittemore said the shuttle's systems were in
excellent condition and the only problems were ``just annoyances.''
   A facsimile machine being tested for sending documents to the
shuttle was shut down when its paper jammed and a machine for
measuring blood pressure failed, he said.
   Atlantis, which rocketed away from Kennedy Space Center on
Thursday afternoon, is scheduled to land Monday at Edwards Air
Force Base, Calif.
</TEXT>
