<DOCNO> AP890506-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1124EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Senegal-Mauritania     05-06 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senegal-Mauritania,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Outbreak of Violence Has Ancient Roots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PODOR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mob violence that has cost the lives of
hundreds of Senegalese and Mauritanians in each other's countries
is rooted in the ancient conflict of nomad and farmer and in the
river that is a lifeline for both.
   Long before a country named Senegal existed, before the enormous
colony called French West Africa was created, the black Toucouleur
people farmed the fertile basin on both sides of the Senegal River.
   Arab-Berber people known as Moors, living to the north in what
became Mauritania, were proud wanderers, herders of camels and
goats who had no interest in a sedentary life on the land.
   When the French left and the two nations were created, the river
became their border.
   Dams have made the basin more valuable, attracting Moorish
investors. Senegalese are being forced from land their forebears
tilled, and new restrictions are being applied to what once was
relatively free cross-border grazing, mostly by Mauritanian herds.
   In Diawara, a riverbank village, a burst of gunfire April 9
killed two Senegalese farmers. Some say Mauritanian border guards
did the shooting, others say Mauritanian tribesmen.
   The incident inspired a spree of reprisal lootings, beatings and
killings in many areas of both countries, particularly the
capitals: Dakar in Senegal and Nouakchott in Mauritania.
   Neither government has given casualty figures. Unofficial counts
indicate about 60 people were killed in Senegal and 200 in
Mauritania and that thousands were wounded.
   So bad did the violence become that Senegal and Mauritania
organized an air shuttle to bring their expatriates home. France,
Algeria, Morocco and Spain contributed planes.
   Neither government wants the conflict. Mustapha Ould
Abedarrahman, Mauritania's information minister, said in an
interview: ``We and Senegal are condemned to cooperate. There are
an enormous amount of things that unite us.''
   Senegalese living in Mauritania do nearly all the fishing,
operate taxis and work as manual laborers.
   Mauritanians have a near-monopoly on small retail business in
Senegal. Every neighborhood has its ``corner Mauritanian'' who
sells products in even the tiniest amounts _ a single cube of sugar
or a handful of rice.
   Both economies are fragile, in a process of restructuring
decreed by the World Bank and International Monetary Fund, and will
suffer from the trouble.
   Historically, peasants in Podor and other villages along the
river have crossed to farm on the Mauritanian side.
   ``That land has belonged to us for centuries,'' said Mamadou
Solih Wone, the Moslem religious leader of Podor and also a farmer.
   ``A Moor doesn't farm,'' Wone said, sitting amid village elders
in a crumbling building on a street of red dirt. ``You will never
see one on the land.''
   ``I have felt this coming for years,'' said Taifour Ibra Wane,
mayor of the dusty town of 12,000.
   Last year, Mauritanian authorities began preventing Senegalese
from farming the other side of the river. Villagers acknowledge
they are crossing an international border but say they have worked
that land for centuries and should be compensated if they are
thrown off it.
   A Senegalese will tell you the historic border was 35 miles or
more north of the river. A Mauritanian will say the frontier was
south of it.
   ``And if it hadn't been for the French,'' an official in
Nouakchott said, ``the Moroccans would have controlled the whole
territory.''
   Mauritanian officials say the river is the border. North of the
river is Mauritania, they say, and if Mauritanians want to farm the
land they have every right to do so.
   All Mauritanian land is in the public domain and the government
will give it to any Mauritanian who wants to develop it.
   Farmers from Senegal say Moors don't want to get their hands
dirty by farming, that they are forming large agricultural
companies and becoming agri-businessmen, profiting from land
developed by Senegalese.
   Dams built near the mouth of the Senegal River at Diama, and at
Manantali in Mali, have brought vast changes. No longer must
farmers hope for an annual flood to soak the land; the dams
guarantee a flood each year.
   Irrigation is possible farther back from the river, making more
land arable and enticing investors. The prospects are of great
interest to Mauritania, which is 99 percent desert.
   ``The white Mauritanians want to take the land from the
Toucouleurs,'' said an agricultural technician who has worked in
the area for 25 years. ``They want all of a sudden to become
farmers and use the blacks as labor as they did with their old
slave system.''
   Senegalese frequently point out that Mauritania did not abolish
slavery until 1980 and that it continues in some areas of the
country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
