<DOCNO> AP890506-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1125EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Congress-Osprey     05-06 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congress-Osprey,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Dogfight Shaping Up Over Marine Corps Aircraft Program</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Dick Cheney faces a major
battle with Congress over the cancellation of the V-22 Osprey
aircraft, which not only is a favorite of the Marine Corps but on
Capitol Hill as well.
   ``Of all the cuts Cheney has proposed the most difficult to get
is the V-22,'' House Armed Services Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis.,
said Friday, hours before the Pentagon announced it would not spend
additional funds to continue the program for another five months.
   ``Stay tuned,'' Aspin said.
   Lawmakers had responded with outrage to Cheney's initial
announcement that he would eliminate the $25.9 billion program
after investing nine years and $2 billion in the battlefield
aircraft designed to take off like a helicopter and fly like an
airplane.
   Cheney called the decision painful but said the program would
have to go as he slashed $10 billion in fiscal 1990 spending under
the budget compromise reached by the White House and Congress.
   Hopes of congressional supporters were raised Thursday when
Deputy Defense Secretary Donald Atwood Jr., indicated the Pentagon
was considering a reprieve for the aircraft as Bell Helicopter
Textron Inc. and Boeing Helicopter Co. threatened to halt work on
the project.
   Late Friday, however, the Pentagon said the V-22 would remain on
the fiscal 1990 budget cutting floor and warned the contractors
that they were expected to complete the work required under their
fiscal 1989 contract. That contract does not expire until Sept. 30.
   The contractors, meanwhile, said they had suspended their threat
of layoffs for the moment, citing the ``strong bipartisan
congressional support for the V-22 program.''
   That support for the Osprey is emerging from the powerful Marine
Corps lobby on Capitol Hill and the concerns of influential
lawmakers, the ranking Republican on the House Armed Services
Committee said Friday.
   ``The Marine lobby per se is as tough as the NRA (National Rifle
Association),'' said Rep. Bill Dickinson of Alabama, who noted that
after the considerable investment the Corps does not want to see
``a wasted effort on their part.''
   Rep. Frank McCloskey, D-Ind., a member of the House Armed
Services Committee, said that ``year after year the Marines have
made the V-22 their highest priority. It's vital to Marine
aviation.''
   The V-22 is a revolutionary aircraft that the Marine Corps wants
to use to improve its ability to conduct surprise, long-range
amphibious assaults. The Pentagon had planned to spend $25.9
billion on 663 Ospreys, including $1.3 billion in 1990.
   The contractors are located in Texas and Pennsylvania, both of
which have large and powerful delegations on Capitol Hill.
   Bell Helicopter Textron is in Fort Worth, Texas _ home district
of House Speaker Jim Wright. Boeing Helicopter Co. is in the home
state for two active defense lawmakers, Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., a
Marine Corps veteran, and Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
   ``I very definitely hear a building crescendo,'' Dickinson said
Friday. ``I raised that point with Dick Cheney. The hottest and
most political issue will be the V-22. I told him to be ready and
expect a firestorm.''
   But lawmakers have begun to suggest other sources of funding to
keep the Osprey program.
   ``Star Wars,'' said McCloskey. ``The thinking is that too much
money is spent on SDI. For $3 billion you can get all the research
and development you need.''
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, said it was too early to tell where the money would come
from, but then mentioned that ``everybody always looks at the SDI
money like the fox looking at the hen house.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
