<DOCNO> AP890506-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1154EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Ollie'sStory Bjt 2takes 05-06 0719</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ollie's Story, Bjt, 2 takes,690-1510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Learned About Defendant in His Own Words</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Oliver North trial had been in progress
for more than two months and his name had been woven through the
testimony like thread through cloth when North finally was called
to the stand.
   ``So you're Colonel North?'' said his lawyer.
   ``Yes, sir,'' said North, with a tight smile.
   ``It's traditional to start with your full name,'' prompted his
lawyer, Brendan Sullivan.
   ``Oliver Laurence, with-a-U, North,'' said the defendant.
   So began six days of questioning in which the 45-year-old North
tried to convince his jury that he was unjustly charged, that the
crimes laid to his feet had honorable roots, that his motives were
righteous and that his actions carried out the wishes of none other
than the president of the United States.
   That he largely succeeded was borne out by Thursday's verdict
which seemed to signal the jury's belief he should be punished only
for those things in which he had total control. Nobody ordered
North to accept an illegal gift _ the security fence around his
home _ and nobody ordered him to mutilate documents that would
expose his machinations.
   ``Did you intend to violate any law by receiving the security
system without paying for it?'' asked Sullivan.
   ``No, I intended to pay for it.``
   ``But did you ever pay for it?''
   ``No, I did not,'' said North.
   Even on the third conviction, creating false chronologies of the
Iran-Contra affair for Congress, the jury found only that he
``aided and abetted'' _ not that he was the principal. In that
charge, too, altering and shredding documents was an element. North
had testified that one of his bosses, former National Security
Adviser Robert McFarlane, had ordered the doctored version.
McFarlane said it wasn't so.
   The Oliver North on the witness stand was not the Oliver North,
seen by millions on television, who told Congress ``I did a lot of
things and I want to stand up and say I'm proud of them.'' Neither
was he the Oliver North of last week's television fiction who so
idolized powerful men that he wound up as everybody's patsy.
   After two years under the Iran-Contra cloud, North had changed.
The boyish brown hair had grayed. His passionate patriotism hadn't
dimmed, but in court it was muted. He was being talked about as if
he had left the room and North reacted by busying himself taking
miles of notes with his left hand. He still knew who the enemy was.
Four days in a row, prosecutor John Keker said, ``Good Morning, Mr.
North'' and the witness pointedly remained mute.
   The six rows of ribbons _ Silver Star for conspicuous gallantry,
Bronze Star marked with V for valor for heroism, Purple Heart for
being twice wounded in action _ had given way to dark suits and
ultra-conservative ties. There was nothing, either, to replace the
presidential service badge that had adorned his right breast in
1987.
   The jury got to know more about North through his own testimony
than through the testimony of others.
   ``How many engagements with the enemy would you have encountered
during your time in Vietnam?'' asked Sullivan.
   ``Oh, I don't know that I never really kept track,'' North
replied. ``Roughly 100 I would suppose.''
   He said that when Congress passed the Boland Amendment in 1984,
forbidding military aid to the guerrillas fighting Nicaragua's
leftist government, ``it was clear that they wanted to find some
way of continuing the support'' _ they, being the White House.
   The CIA, he said, had been providing everything ``from the
little tents that they lived in, to the homes that they had for
their children, to the food they ate, the weapons they carried, the
bullets they had _ everything had come form the CIA. All of the
intelligence, all of the operations planning.''
   Q. What did you understand your assignment to be?
   A. I understood it very clearly to be that I would be the one to
replace the CIA for each of these activities.
   But what about the Boland Amendment? ``I talked to Director
Casey. I talked to Mr. McFarlane. I talked to the NSC lawyers ...
none of them thought that it applied to the NSC.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890506-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Ollie'sStory Bjt 1stadd 05-06 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ollie's Story, Bjt, 1st add,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHN: the NSC.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   North said William Casey, the CIA director, told him a man to
help him accomplish what he was after was Richard Secord, a retired
Air Force major general with expertise in running covert supply
operations.
   ``He started out basically delivering munitions. I mean, that
was the first step. He became a person who arranged for the
shipping of the munitions out of Europe. ... It then expanded to
include air delivery of those munitions. He was eventually in the
process of building warehouses at various airfields around Central
America that could do these things, because we couldn't use any of
the U.S. government facilities that had been set up under the CIA.
We tried very hard to stay within the line that was drawn by
Boland.''
   Casey also gave him the names of people to work with in Central
America.
   Q. Whenever you had such a contact with an official of a
neighboring country in Central America, would you always have the
permission of your superiors?
   A. Yes, sir. I never made a single trip down there ... never
made single contact with anybody down there without the permission,
express permission of either Mr. McFarlane or Admiral Poindexter,
and, usually, when I could, with the concurrence of Director Casey.
   And, asked Sullivan, did President Regan himself act to help the
freedom fighters ``for example, by calling the presidents of
foreign countries?''
   Yes, sir, said North.
   What about the fund-raising he was accused of?
   ``I was told specifically that I could not, personally, me,
Ollie North, ask them for money, that I was a government official.
... I never recall a single instance where a donor, a person who
has shown up now in these lists of names, who gave money, ever gave
money in my presence, was ever asked to give money in my presence.''
   Q. You are accused in this case, Colonel North, of conspiracy to
commit a tax fraud. Did you do so?
   A. No, sir. I did not.
   North said that when Congress asked for information in 1985
about his activities, McFarlane, then the national security adviser
told him to alter six memos dealing with raising money from third
countries and details of NSC military assistance to the Contras.
   He said he didn't get around to doing that until the Iran-Contra
connection became known a year later when, he said, McFarlane
asked, ``Did you ever take care of that other stuff way back when,
what did you do with that or words to that effect.
   ``I said, well, I haven't taken care of it yet, but I will. And
then I went and had the documents pulled from the files and altered
them consistent with what he had earlier asked me to do.''
   Sullivan: Did you believe it was unlawful to do that?
   North: No, I had written those documents. I had prepared them
for him. They were his documents. It never occurred to me that that
could be unlawful.
   Sullivan: When you didn't disclose information they were looking
at, did you believe your conduct was unlawful.
   North: I was raised to know the difference between right and
wrong. I knew it wasn't right not to tell the truth on those
things, but I didn't think it was unlawful.
   Others had hesitated to attack North because of his war record.
But not prosecutor John Keker, who was _ like North _ wounded as a
Marine officer in Vietnam.
   Keker needled North by intimating he had violated the honor code
he was taught at the U.S. Naval Academy.
   ``In the United States Naval Academy you would be kicked out for
this, wouldn't you?'' he asked at one point.
   ``In the United States Naval Academy nobody taught me how to
deal with running a covert operation, Mr. Keker,'' North shot back.
``Nobody taught me how to run a covert operation in the Marine
Corps. I was trying my everloving best to get it done and the fact
is that nobody in the United States Naval Academy teaches you about
the internecine political warfare that was going on in Washington
from 1983 to 1986.''
   Keker: Did any moral bell go off in your head?
   North: It wouldn't be proper for me to describe it as a moral
bell. I thought it was extraordinarily immoral to have fielded a
force (the Contras), put it in the field, equipped it, trained it,
fed it, clothed it, armed it, sent it into combat and then left it
in the lurch. I thought it was heinous.''
   North seemed particularly stung by Keker's assertion in his
closing argument that North and McFarlane had been ``following
Adolf Hitler's old strategy: The victor will never be asked if he
told the truth.''
   On Thursday, after the verdict, North read a statement to
reporters recalling that Keker ``has likened me to Adolf Hitler.''
   Said North: ``As a Marine, I was taught to fight and fight hard
for as long as it takes to prevail. We will continue this battle.''
</TEXT>
