<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--AIDS-Africa     05-06 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--AIDS-Africa,0186</SECOND>
<UNK>WHO Official Calls for Confidential AIDS reporting in Africa</UNK>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.N. official proposed African countries
make confidential reports on the spread of AIDS in their countries
to encourage more accurate information on the disease, a news
report said Saturday.
   Lobe Monekosso, the U.N. World Health Organization's director
for Africa, said current reporting on the spread of AIDS in Africa
is ``haphazard, irregular and underestimated,'' the Standard
newspaper said.
   ``Most African countries do not want to be associated with AIDS
or are shy about divulging the real numbers of cases,'' Monekosso
said. ``I propose we adopt semi-confidential reporting.''
   Monekosso said the number of people in Africa infected with
acquired immune deficiency syndrome could be as high as 1 million.
   Last month, WHO reported 10,918 cases of AIDS in Africa.
   There is no known cure for AIDS, which attacks the body's immune
system.
   In the United States and Europe, AIDS has been largely confined
to male homosexuals, hemophiliacs and intravenous drug abusers. In
Africa, it is believed to be transmitted primarily through
heterosexual contact.
</TEXT>
