<HEAD>Vietnamese Boat People Arrive in Hong Kong</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five boats filled with 278 Vietnamese refugees
reached Hong Kong on Saturday, bringing to more than 1,600 the
number of boat people arriving here this month, officials said.
   More than 5,800 boat people have traveled to the British colony
since January, Alistair Aspery, Hong Kong's acting secretary for
security, told reporters.
   He said the government was running out of room for the refugees.
Four ferries were hired as temporary shelter for 1,200 Vietnamese,
he said.
   On Wednesday, Geoffrey Barnes, Hong Kong's head of security,
said he expected 11,000 Vietnamese boat people to arrive in the
next months. Typically, there is an upsurge in refugees in the
spring and summer.
   There are more than 30,000 Vietnamese boat people in Hong Kong.
