<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-06 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michelle Fowler's prom date was 48
years older than she is, but the Stonewall Jackson High senior
didn't mind.
   Fowler, 17, took her grandfather, 65-year-old John Samuels, to
the prom Friday night, saying it was an appropriate way both to
express her love for him and to mark the school's final prom.
   ``I feel honored that he would go with me,'' Fowler said. ``I
thought he'd say no. I thought he wouldn't want to go with a bunch
of high school kids.''
   Stonewall Jackson is merging with Charleston High this summer to
form Capital High.
   Samuels is a 1941 Stonewall Jackson graduate who did not attend
his senior prom. However, he traveled from Florida to West Virginia
for Friday night's four-hour prom cruise aboard the West Virginia
Belle sternwheeler.
   ``I was in the first graduating class, and she thought it would
be something by her being in the last,'' Samuels said of his
granddaughter, to whom he gave his 1941 class ring last summer.
   ``Grandpa was really good to me as I was growing up,'' Fowler
said. ``We were always really good friends _ not just granddaughter
and grandpa. I'd rather go with him than some ol' guy.
   The couple made all the proper prom plans.
   ``I rented a tux and she got a dress,'' Samuels said. ``I
ordered the flowers.''
   The only thing that worried Samuels was his dancing ability.
   ``I told her to get a backup, but she still wanted me to go with
her,'' he said. ``I couldn't shake and rattle like these kids can
today.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BILOXI, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first of the new Biloxi schooner
sailboats is in the water, bringing back memories of the vessels
that once turned the Mississippi Coast city into the
self-proclaimed Seafood Capital of the World.
   Eighty-seven-year-old Glenn Swetman smiled broadly as the boat
that carries his name plunged into Back Bay on Friday from a
boatyard in D'Iberville, across the bay from here.
   The sailboat was named for him because his bank made a large
contribution to the private effort to bring back the era of sailing
schooners here. Eventually, the 68-foot, two-masted Glenn L.
Swetman will be joined by a second, as-yet-unnamed schooner.
   In the late 19th and early 20th centuries, the schooners
harvested Gulf shrimp and oysters, and raced one another in the
off-seasons.
   Both the seafood title and the fishing fleets became victims of
change when motorized boats began scooping up a depleting bounty,
and schooners largely disappeared by the 1930s.
   The Glenn L. Swetman won't be scooping up shrimp and oysters,
but it will race and earn its keep as a charter and educational
boat.
   The schooner project, begun in 1986, and a seafood industry
museum are part of an effort to revive the Biloxi waterfront.
   ``Now this is true progress with preservation _ bringing back
historic boats as a symbol of our revival,'' said Biloxi Mayor
Gerald Blessey as he watched the schooner slip into the water. ``We
are already getting requests for charters for this boat, even for
convention parties.''
   Numerous fund-raisers, private contributions and an $80,000 bank
loan have footed the bill for the $200,000 schooner.
</TEXT>
