<FIRST>r i AM-Poland     05-06 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike By Polish Copper Miners Enters Its Second Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper workers from the official trade
union alliance and from Solidarity struck four mines in
southwestern Poland for a second day Saturday to demand higher pay.
   Jan Sugalski, a local Solidarity activist, said the miners were
demanding a 50 percent pay increase. He said they earn $118 to $176
a month.
   Sugalski said the miners formed a strike committee of
representatives from the official trade union alliance, OPZZ, and
the recently legalized Solidarity union. Talks between the
committee and management have so far failed to settle the strike,
the state news agency PAP said.
   A seven-year ban on Solidarity was lifted April 17 under an
agreement the opposition and communist authorities reached during
broad-based talks that were held after a serious wave of strikes
last year.
   Workers were striking at the Lubin, Polkowice, Rudna and
Sieroszowice mines near the city of Lubin, 200 miles southwest of
Warsaw, Sugalski and PAP said.
   Sugalski said more than 20,000 miners joined the strike, which
began Friday morning. PAP said the miners struck the morning shift
and were joined by workers on the afternoon shift. PAP gave no
figures on the number of strikers.
   Sugalski said the striking miners remained on the surface of the
pits and were carrying out maintenance underground.
   On Friday, the strikers handed over a list of demands, all of
which concerned pay, and they were rejected by management, he said.
</TEXT>
