<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Richard M. Daley presented David Letterman
with a genuine, soiled manhole cover Friday as the NBC talk-show
host ended four days of ``Late Night'' in Chicago.
   ``I know you have an interest in our sewer system,'' Daley told
Letterman, referring to remote-camera footage from inside the
city's sewer system that was featured on Letterman's show earlier
in the week.
   Letterman accepted the metal, saying, ``Oh, a little heavy
there.''
   He welcomed the new mayor, who took office last month, on stage
by telling him how much he enjoyed having the show broadcast from
Chicago.
   The ``people of Chicago are nice, automatically nice,
automatically friendly, polite, that the city is apparently
thriving, that it's clean, and that it's relatively safe ... .''
   Daley finally broke in: ``Are you running for mayor?''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRANSON, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are no more wasted days or wasted
nights for Freddy Fender, the country music singer says, now that
he has kicked drugs and alcohol and started work on reviving his
career.
   ``For the last 3{ years, I've been hellbent ... trying to catch
up after 10 years of drugs and alcohol,'' Fender said Friday in an
interview with The Springfield News-Leader. ``We're working very
hard on getting there.''
   Fender, who is performing six nights a week in the 800-seat
theater at the Kirkwood Inn, said he was driven to drugs and
alcohol at the height of his success in the 1970s.
   ``Fame can kill you,'' he said. ``Fame has killed a lot of
artists. The big one is the drugs and alcohol. For some reason,
it's so natural.''
   Fender's single ``Before the Next Teardrop Falls'' reached No. 1
on the charts in 1975. He followed with ``Wasted Days and Wasted
Nights,'' becoming one of the major country stars of the 1970s to
find a mainstream audience.
   He said he didn't start to recuperate until his wife obtained a
court order four years ago to commit him to a treatment center.
   His first recording in eight years, ``Spanish Harlem,'' is to be
released this spring by Critique-Atlantic Records. He is also cast
in ``Desperado,'' an upcoming NBC miniseries.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music star Ricky Skaggs and his
wife and singing partner, Sharon White, are the parents of their
second child.
   Lukas Buck Skaggs was born Thursday at Nashville Memorial
Hospital, weighing 9 pounds and 9 ounces, spokeswoman Judi Turner
said. Mother and son were reported healthy.
   The couple also have a 5-year-old daughter, Molly Kate, and
Skaggs has a son and a daughter from a previous marriage.
   Lukas Buck was named after White's father, country music singer
Buck White.
   Skaggs, whose hits include ``Country Boy,'' and his wife were
voted duo of the year in 1987 by the Country Music Association.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jerry Lewis' 38-year-old wife,
who was two months pregnant, has lost the child, Lewis' manager
said Saturday.
   Sandi Lewis was examined Thursday by a Los Angeles doctor who
conducted a sonogram test that revealed the baby's heart was not
beating, manager Joe Stabile said.
   Mrs. Lewis is recuperating at the couple's Las Vegas home.
   Lewis, 63, learned that his wife was pregnant a month ago during
a break in a show at the Olympia Theater in Paris, and he told
audience he was going to be ``a proud papa.''
   The two have been married six years and have no children.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steven Ford, the newest member of the
National Cowboy Hall of Fame's board of directors, remembers the
day he told his father, then-President Ford, he wanted to go west
and become a cowboy.
   ``I had never even really ridden a horse,'' Ford said Friday,
``and it was probably the silliest thing ever said in the Oval
Office. But we worked out a deal where if I didn't make it, I would
go back to school the next year.
   ``I just look back and say, `It was the best decision I ever
made.'''
   Ford worked after high school on a Utah ranch and studied animal
science at California Polytechnical University.
   He got into acting because ``when I was 21, 22, I had some
friends who needed someone who could fall off a horse, so I went to
do some work in the movie `Cattle Annie and Little Britches,''' he
said during a tour of the Cowboy Hall.
   Ford, 32, said he is taking a year off from acting after seven
years on the soap opera ``The Young and The Restless.''
   He will represent the state of California on the hall's board of
directors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Comedian Jonathan Winters may be serious
about artistic painting, but not that serious.
   ``There's much more to it than having paints, a large bottle of
vodka and a TV set locked on the `Days of Our Lives,''' said
Winters, who was in San Francisco Saturday to receive a doctor of
humane letters degree from the Academy of Art College.
   But consider some of the wacky titles he's chosen for some of
his work.
   ``Pathetic Black Moon with Awful Vase with Dead Flowers in It,''
is what Winters called a ``put-on of a large white canvas with a
little red dot on its center that the Museum of Modern Art in New
York paid 200 grand for.''
   Then there's ``Two Birds Watching Doris Day's Cat and Dog
Drown.'' Winters said that while Day is involved in various animal
protection causes, the painting has nothing to do with her.
Instead, it's ``just my black humor at work.''
   Winters, 63, studied art at Kenyon College in Gambier, Ohio, and
the Dayton Art Institute. He holds a bachelor of fine arts degree
from Dayton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
