<FIRST>u w AM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0531 05-06 0843</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0531,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 10th graf to clarify Bush status in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>``For Dan Quayle, No News is Good News,'' Says Trip Analyst</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle emerged from his
latest on-the-job training trip relatively unscathed by public
criticism, happy about his personal contact with world leaders and
insisting he is ready to make a difference in foreign affairs.
   Returning to the nation's capital Friday after 12 days in which
he saw Australia, Indonesia, Singapore and Thailand, Quayle said
information he garnered abroad will help him play a role in
formulating policies in the Bush administration.
   Even though ``I don't sign treaties,'' Quayle said, ``I
guarantee you what I learned on this trip ... will help make
policy.'' One area in which he is expected to have input involves
Cambodia where Vietnamese troops are scheduled to end their
decade-long occupation Sept. 30.
   Quayle said his second foreign excursion as vice president _ his
first was in February to Venezuela and El Salvador _ gave him an
understanding of a range of issues as well as the personalities who
shape them.
   ``I am now in personal contact with those leaders,'' he said.
   The trip was full of exotic photo opportunities: Quayle mingling
with sarong-clad women Pago Pago; Quayle golfing with Singapore's
deputy prime minister; Quayle in a coverall touring an oil-slick
beach in Alaska; Quayle cuddling Cambodian refugees in a camp six
miles from the Thai-Cambodian border.
   He even tried scuba diving on Australia's Great Barrier Reef.
   The vice president's tour bore similarities to one President
Bush made in the spring of 1982 when he was vice president. Bush
visited Australia, Singapore, Japan, South Korea and China.
   But Larry Sabato, a political science professor at the
University of Virginia, said Quayle's trip was more important for
him because Bush already had wide experience in foreign affairs
when he became vice president.
   Bush was a former head of the CIA, ambassador to the United
Nations and chief U.S. liaison officer to China, a rank tantamount
to ambassador, during the establishment of full diplomatic
relations with the communist nation.
   Quayle is a former senator from Indiana with limited experience
in foreign affairs, although he is well-versed in defense policy.
   Before the recent trip, Japan was the only Pacific country
Quayle had visited.
   Sabato said trips like Quayle's are crucial to expand his
breadth of knowledge and let Americans, particularly the vice
president's conservative Republican supporters, know he can handle
himself as a diplomat.
   ``This is on-the-job training,'' Sabato said. Such trips help
Quayle as long as he doesn't make any major mistakes, he said.
``For Dan Quayle, no news is good news.''
   Abroad as at home, Quayle attracts interest, Sabato said, from
people who want to know whether he's really the way Democratic
opponents portrayed him as in the 1988 election campaign: a
wet-behind-the-ears, good-natured sports buff without the
intellectual facilities necessary to lead the largest nation in the
free world.
   ``He's viewed as a curiosity,'' Sabato said.
   Nowhere was more attention paid to Quayle than in Australia,
where he had a well-publicized run-in with officials over subsidies
the United States pays to its wheat farmers. The Australians say
price supports hurt their exports abroad; Quayle says they don't,
and besides, they're aimed at protectionist policies in Europe, not
Australia.
   ``It's a very sensitive issue with the Australians,'' the vice
president said.
   In a column in the Sydney Morning News the day after Quayle
arrived, Tony Stephens wrote that Quayle apparently had chosen to
visit Australia because it was a friendly nation.
   ``The rationale for this piece of diplomacy was Mr. Quayle's
bumbling effort in the presidential campaign,'' he wrote, ``Now,
however, Mr. Quayle is apparently growing into his job.''
   Another writer _ in the national newspaper The Australian _ said
the Australian national press corps ``clearly enjoyed Mr. Quayle's
brand of humor'' in an appearance at Canberra's National Press Club.
   Australia was the place Quayle said he would have liked more
time, particularly Canberra, the capital. There, Quayle, a
self-described member of a ``new generation'' of world leaders,
said he enjoyed seeing contemporaries like 40-year-old Defense
Minister Kim Beazley.
   The vice president acknowledged he played down his ``new
generation'' theme in Thailand and Indonesia, two countries with a
layer of older leaders.
   In Indonesia, Quayle met with human rights activists but
refrained from publicly criticizing President Suharto on the issue.
   In Singapore, Quayle said he had a ``long and profound''
discussion with Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew about press freedom and
human rights in that small, bustling city-state.
   In Jakarta, Indonesia, Quayle highlighted his talks with Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, a former Cambodian head of state who resides
there. Sihanouk, leader of the non-communist resistance, is favored
by Washington to lead a transition government in Cambodia. The
United States is weighing whether to give him military aid.
   Meantime, Quayle's aides are planning his next foreign foray,
possibly to Africa in the fall. Quayle said he also wants to see
more of Latin America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
