<DOCNO> AP890506-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Bolivia-Elections     05-06 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolivia-Elections,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Dictator Ahead in Bolivian Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former military dictator is the
front-runner in elections Sunday to choose a president for this
largely Indian nation plagued by poverty and drugs.
   More than 2 million Bolivians are to choose from among nine
candidates vying to replace President Victor Paz Estenssoro, who is
retiring at age 81.
   Most polls have placed former dictator Gen. Hugo Banzer Suarez
of the rightist Nationalist Democratic Action in front, with
Gonzalo Sanchez de Lozada of the conservative Revolutionary
Nationalist Movement competing for second place with Jaime Paz
Zamora of the Social Democratic Movement of the Revolutionary Left.
   Six other candidates were expected to garner only a small
percentage of the vote.
   Voters also will choose representatives for all 27 senate seats
and all 130 house seats.
   On Saturday, multcolored ballots were being distributed at the
more than 8,000 polling places across the nation of 6.7 million
people. The large single-sheet ballots bear party colors to help
the 37 percent of Bolivians who are illiterate cast votes.
   ``It is being carried out in a well-organized and transparent
manner,'' said Estela Rios de Jurada of El Salvador, one of more
than 20 foreign observers in Bolivia for the vote.
   Herman Antelo, Bolivia's information minister, said the
elections demonstrate the country's political maturity.
   It was likely, however, that the final word on who would be the
next president would come from the new congress when it convenes
Aug. 4.
   Under the constitution, a candidate must win an absolute
majority to become president by popular vote. If no candidate wins
more than 35 percent of the vote, congress can choose among the top
three. Polls indicated no candidate would win more than 35 percent.
   Banzer finished first in the last presidential election in 1985,
with 28.6 percent of the vote, but congress picked the second-place
finisher, Paz Estenssoro, who received 26.4 percent.
   Banzer seized power in a bloody coup in 1971 that toppled a
leftist military dictatorship. He ruled until 1978, when popular
pressure obliged him to call elections. The Bolivian Rights
Assembly says that during Banzer's government there were political
murders, 78 disappearences, and 14,537 illegal detentions.
   Sanchez de Lozada, a University of Chicago philosophy graduate,
promised to create 250,000 new jobs and 150,000 new dwellings. He
was planning minister under Paz Estenssoro and one of the
architects of an economic stabilization program that lowered
inflation from 24,000 percent four years ago to 2 percent for the
first quarter of this year.
   Few differences have emerged during the campaign. All the
candidates have pledged to continue the economic measures, though
their social cost has been high. They included the firing of 35,000
state-contracted miners and other public workers. Unemployment is
at 23 percent and the monthly minimum wage is $45.
   The candidates also pledged to continue the government's war on
cocaine production and trafficking, a flourishing illegal industry
that brings in $200 million to $300 million a year, according to
government estimates. Legal exports are expected to bring in only
$600 million this year.
   An estimated 300,000 Bolivians depend on coca leaf farming,
cocaine processing or trafficking for their livelihood, government
figures show. Coca leaves are the raw ingredient in cocaine.
   Paz Estenssoro's government has relied heavily on U.S.
assistance in its war on drugs. The United States provides about
$10 million yearly for drug programs, 50 military trainers, drug
enforcement agents and border patrol police.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
