<DOCNO> AP890506-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1642EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Unrest     05-06 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Round of Armenian Protest Breaks Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Armenians have launched a new wave of protests to
demand annexation of a disputed enclave and freedom for activists
arrested in ethnic unrest, residents and officials said Saturday.
   A strike beginning Wednesday closed all businesses in
Stepanakert, the administrative center of the disputed
Nagorno-Karabakh area, said Valery A. Sidorov, a government
official there. Only medical clinics, food-processing plants, and
the power station remained open, he said in a telephone interview.
   The strikers are demanding that authorities in Moscow reconsider
their January decision to place Nagorno-Karabakh under Kremlin
control, Sidorov said. The strikers, who are mostly ethnic
Armenians, want to wrest the region from Azerbaijan and incorporate
it into the neighboring Armenian republic.
   The region in the Caucasus Mountains in the southwestern Soviet
Union has been part of Azerbaijan since 1923. Armenians, who make
up three-quarters of the region's 162,000 people, say they suffer
discrimination by Azerbaijanis.
   Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh and the Armenian Republic carried
out strikes and demonstrations through most of last year until the
earthquake in December that killed an estimated 25,000 people. More
than 90 people were killed in the ethnic unrest.
   Sidorov said a group of local party officials wrote an open
letter published in the Nagorno-Karabakh press asking for a meeting
with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to discuss the dispute.
   Rafael Popoyan, an activist in Yerevan, said people also went on
strike to protest reports that the official in charge of
Nagorno-Karabakh, Arkady Volsky, ordered that more ethnic
Azerbaijanis be settled in the region. They now comprise 23 percent
of the region's population.
   However, Sidorov said there has been no influx of Azerbaijanis
and that Armenians instead have been moving to the area.
   Two residents reported that a crowd of Armenians formed in
Yerevan, the Armenian capital, on Saturday night to demand that
authorities free 11 activists. The prisoners belong to the Karabakh
Committee, which spearheaded the drive for Nagorno-Karabakh's
alliance with Armenia.
   The activists were arrested in December, but authorities have
not announced any charges against them.
   Silva Arutunyan, an Armenian poet who went to the gathering,
estimated the crowd at 50,000. But Armen Minasyan, a ninth grade
teacher who also there, put the figure at 1,000 to 2,000. The
official Soviet news media carried no report of the protest.
   The two residents, both speaking by telephone, said the crowd
dispersed after about 90 minutes when a speaker announced that
another meeting would be held Thursday.
   Popoyan, also speaking by telephone, said Armenian television
had broadcast warnings Friday threatening that ``all available
means'' would be used to control protests. Police and troops were
posted at two popular demonstrations sites in downtown Yerevan to
block demonstrations, he said.
   Yerevan and the Azerbaijani capital, Baku, were placed under
martial law and public gatherings were banned in November because
of the ethnic violence. A curfew enforced by troops remains in
effect.
</TEXT>
