<FIRST>r a AM-WinerySlayings     05-06 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Winery Slayings,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Attorney Says Salcido's Return to U.S. Was Illegal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The attorney for a former winery
worker charged with seven slayings said Sonoma County authorities
illegally brought Ramon Salcido back from Mexico to stand trial.
   Public Defender Marteen Miller said Friday that he would file
legal papers challenging ``the manner in which (Salcido) was
transported back to this country and the violation of a treaty''
with Mexico.
   After a brief Santa Rosa Municipal Court hearing in which
Salcido pleaded innocent to the seven counts of murder, Miller said
he would make his appeal before a preliminary hearing scheduled to
start Sept. 11.
   Salcido, 28, is charged with murdering his wife, two daughters,
mother-in-law, two sisters-in-law and a co-worker at the Grand Cru
winery near his Boyes Hot Springs home on April 14.
   Salcido's three daughters were found in a Sonoma County dump
with their throats slashed. One daughter, 3-year-old Carmina,
survived and remains under medical care at Petaluma Valley Hospital.
   Salcido was apprehended in his native Mexico by Mexican police
who were aided by the U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration.
   International treaties prevent criminal suspects from being
extradited from Mexico without hearings. Even so, Mexican officials
deported Salcido without a hearing, and he was flown back to Santa
Rosa with sheriff's deputies on a private jet belonging to
``Peanuts'' cartoonist Charles Schulz.
   Miller declined to say what action he might take if the judge
agrees Salcido's return to the U.S. was illegal. Theoretically, he
could ask that Salcido be returned to Mexico or ask that charges be
dismissed.
   Miller contends that an impartial trial is impossible in Sonoma
County.
   Salcido is kept in an isolated cell at the county jail, under
24-hour supervision that acts as a suicide watch.
   A gag order has been issued forbidding court and law enforcement
authorities from discussing the case with reporters.
</TEXT>
