<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1703EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-AirCrash     05-06 0496</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Air Crash,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Minister Dies in Air Crash, Thousands Attend Funeral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALAH NASRAWI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Adnan Khairallah, defense minister for
10 years and President Saddam Hussein's closest confidant, was
killed in an air crash during a sandstorm in northern Iraq, the
government said Saturday.
   The Iraqi leader, in a statement broadcast by the state radio
and television, said the pilot of the helicopter flying the
50-year-old general to Baghdad on Friday lost control during the
storm and the aircraft crashed.
   Khairallah's body was brought Saturday to the capital, where
thousands of mourners took part in a state funeral led by his
father, Khairallah Telfah, and the Iraqi leader. He later was
buried at the family cemetery in Tikrit, his birthplace and
Saddam's hometown.
   Khairallah, deputy commander in chief of the armed forces, was
considered the second most powerful man after the president in the
tight-knit clan that rules Iraq. He was both a cousin and
brother-in-law to Saddam.
   Saddam said Khairallah died instantly when the helicopter went
down en route to Baghdad from the northern mountain resort of
Sarsang near Mosul. Mosul is 280 miles northwest of Baghdad.
   He said everyone on board was killed, except one person
hospitalized, but did not say how many. The statement said two
escorting helicopters survived ``the crazy storm.'' The site of the
crash was not reported.
   The Iraqi leader gave no further details. The helicopter was
believed to be one of the U.S.-built Bell helicopters that the
president and his aides normally use when traveling in Iraq.
   Khairallah was appointed defense minister in 1979, days after
Saddam assumed the presidency, and held the post throughout the
eight-year Iran-Iraq war that halted with a cease-fire last August.
   The president described him as ``one of the distingushed war
heroes and a sparkling star in Iraq's sky.''
   Khairallah was born in Tikrit, 115 miles north of Baghdad, in
1939 and joined the army in 1959. The president was raised by
Khairallah's father, his mother's brother, and married Khairallah's
sister, Sajdeh.
   Diplomats in Baghdad this year told a visiting reporter that the
two had a brief falling out last fall over the president's
treatment of his eldest son, Odai.
   They said Saddam's wife protested when the president ordered a
public trial for Odai for killing a favorite presidential bodyguard
in October.
   The diplomats said she considered the killing a tragic accident,
not a crime, and asked her brother to intervene with the president.
   Khairallah was a member of the ruling Revolutionary Command
Council and the highest command of the ruling Baath Party.
   He took part in the bloodless coup that brought the party to
power in 1968, when he was a young captain in an armored brigade.
   The tanks under his command surrounded the presidential palace
to force then-president Abdul Rahaman Aref to step down.
   Khairallah was married to the daughter of ex-president Ahmed
Hassan Bakr, who resigned in 1979. He had three children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
