<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Reax     05-06 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Reax,0637</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain, France, Israel Join United States in Condemning Iran</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain and France accused Iran on Saturday of
inciting murder by urging Palestinians to wage an international
campaign of terror against Westerners in retaliation for slayings
in Israel's occupied lands.
   Israel's Foreign Ministry called the Iranian appeal ``a
bloodthirsty idea.''
   Britain said it would discuss the threat with European and
American allies, and the government tightened security at airports
in London and Manchester. There were no other indications of what
steps Western governments might take to counter the Iranian threat.
   The United States condemned Iran for the remarks on Friday. The
United States, Britain and France were singled out as targets in an
inflammatory speech Friday by Iran's Parliament Speaker Hashemi
Rafsanjani.
   Rafsanjani urged Palestinians to kill five Americans, Britons or
Frenchmen for every Arab slain in the uprising in Israeli-occupied
territories. He urged Palestinians to hijack planes or blow up
factories in Western countries to pressure Israel to release
prisoners.
   Rafsanjani also denounced the peace initiative of Palestine
Liberation Organization leader Yasser Arafat, who has renounced
terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist.
   Rafsanjani once was regarded as a moderate. His remarks
underlined a new and growing anti-Western trend that is part of a
radical resurgence in Iran.
   The British Foreign Office said, ``The incitement to murder of
British citizens or those of any other country is totally
unacceptable.
   ``It is ... an affront to international standards of behavior
and further confirmation, if any were necessary, that Iran is not
ready to accept its international obligations,'' it said.
   Home Office Minister Timothy Renton said he was certain all
Moslems in Britain would reject Rafsanjani's call. ``I was
horrified ... and I'm sure every law-abiding Moslem, Christian and
Jew in this and any other Western country will be horrified too,''
he told Independent Television News.
   In Paris, the French Foreign Ministry said in a statement that
Rafsanjani's declarations ``are totally unacceptable because they
accompany an inadmissible call to murder.''
   ``They are of a nature to create the presumption of
responsibility of Iran in all violent action which could now
come,'' the ministry said.
   In Washington on Friday, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater
denounced Rafsanjani's comments as ``another step backwards for
Iran from the community of civilized nations.'' He said the United
States held the Iranian leadership responsible for any attacks on
American interests or citizens.
   PLO representative Faisal Aweidah in London said he did not
think Rafsanjani's appeal would mobilize many militants in Britain.
   In Paris, Ayatollah Mehdi Rouhani, spiritual leader of the
Shiite community in Europe, said: ``The irresponsible and
anti-Islamic words spoken by Mr. Rafsanjani regarding the free
world prove that the extremist tendency has scored decisive points
in Iran.''
   He said Iran ``has been thrown into the extreme leftist camp.''
   Shiite Moslems predominate in Iran.
   The British Department of Transport issued an urgent directive
to airport authorities advising extreme caution. Its contents were
not disclosed, but a department spokesman said on condition of
anonymity that the agency was taking the threats ``very seriously''
and had initiated ``appropriate measures.''
   Extra staffers were sent to several airports on Saturday,
including Gatwick near London, to make increased checks on
passengers.
   A Gatwick spokeswoman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the precautions had led to some minor holdups.
   A spokeswoman at London's Heathrow Airport also reported slight
delays as a result of the security measures. She said the
Department of Transport had provided detailed instructions, which
were followed to the letter.
   At Manchester Airport, the Sunday Times said police armed with
handguns and submachine guns were seen for the first time in three
years.
</TEXT>
