<FIRST>r a AM-SecondAbduction     05-06 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction,0683</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sheriff Obsessed With Infant's Disappearance, Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff investigating the three-year-old
death of a baby whose parents reported was abducted said Saturday
that the strangely similar slaying of another daughter gives him
hope he'll make arrests.
   Jersey County Sheriff Frank Yocom, 50, said he still thinks
daily about the June 1986 death of Loralei Marie Sims, which left
him angry and upset. ``It's worn on me,'' Yocom said.
   ``I've maintained throughout my investigation that I would never
close the case as long as I was involved in law enforcement in
Jersey County, make arrests and put this thing to rest,'' he said.
``And that's still my goal.''
   The parents, Robert and Paula Sims, are the chief suspects in
the latest case, the death of their 6-week-old daughter Heather
Lee, and authorities expect to make an arrest soon, police Sgt.
Rick McCain said Friday in this city of 40,000 people along the
Mississippi River near St. Louis.
   McCain said Saturday that neither parent is considered the
stronger suspect.
   The Simses deny any wrongdoing, and hope police will investigate
``with an open mind so the killer will be caught,'' said their
attorney, Donald Groshong of Alton. The parents have refused to
talk to reporters.
   The state Department of Children and Family Services on Friday
took custody of their 15-month-old son, Randy, and the parents are
staying with relatives.
   Their home in a middle-income, tree-lined neighborhood remains
an object of curiosity.
   Broken glass, remnants from Thursday night when authorities
broke a window to get inside the house, is still scattered on the
front porch, and the grass stands about a foot high.
   A sign on the front door reads: ``In case of fire, save our
dogs. We have dogs.''
   Officials investigating Heather's death have examined Jersey
County records, and have been working closely with Yocom, the
sheriff said by telephone from his office in Jerseyville.
   When authorities interviewed Robert Sims, 37, on Thursday night,
Yocom sat in. Sims ``made some comments that could be very helpful
down the road,'' the sheriff said.
   In June 1986, the parents, who then lived in nearby Brighton in
Jersey County, reported that an armed intruder barged into their
home while Sims was at work and took Loralei, their 13-day-old
firstborn.
   Remains believed to be Loralei's were found a week later near
the couple's former home. The parents were suspects, but no one was
charged.
   On April 29, the Simses told police that a masked gunman knocked
out Mrs. Sims, 30, and abducted Heather.
   Four days later, a fisherman found the child's body, which was
wrapped in a black plastic bag, in a trash barrel at a West Alton,
Mo., recreation area along the Mississippi River.
   It appeared the body had been refrigerated, and an autopsy
determined that Heather had died of asphyxiation about the time she
was reported missing, McCain said.
   Yocom said that when heard the scenario, he felt there was no
question anything ``could be that bizarre.''
   Hair samples were taken from a freezer at the home of Mrs. Sims'
parents, Orville and Nylene Blew, who were out of town the night
Heather was reported kidnapped, Yocom said. Tests are being done to
determine if the hair matches Heather's.
   Investigators also seized from the Blew home an infant's sleeper
that Heather was believed to have been wearing at the time of the
abduction, McCain said.
   In Loralei's case, however, evidence was lacking, Yocom said.
   ``You couldn't even call it a murder because the body was in
such bad shape,'' he said.
   The sheriff said he still gets weekly inquiries about the case,
and still feels pressure to solve it.
   In Alton, too, some folks are growing restless.
   ``That's all everybody is talking about now,'' said Jeanette
O'Dell, 67, who lives near the Simses. ``Every time somebody hears
something new, I get a phone call.''
</TEXT>
