<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1933EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope     05-06 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Arrives Home After 9-Day African Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II ended a nine-day African visit
Saturday by telling Africans to reject the modern way of life and
instead embrace their own traditions and Christianity.
   The pope arrived back in Rome aboard a special Alitalia Boeing
747 after celebrating Mass for 75,000 people in Lilongwe, Malawi's
administrative capital. A group of Impi warriors wearing leopard
skins and carrying spears danced as he boarded the plane.
   John Paul's 41st foreign pilgrimage and fifth trip to Africa
covered 13,500 miles, taking him to the African island of
Madagascar, the French Indian Ocean island of Reunion, Zambia and
Malawi.
   In a papal first, John Paul flew on the supersonic Concorde,
traveling at more than twice the speed of sound from Reunion to
Zambia.
   But in the homily of his final Mass, the pope told Africans not
to abandon their roots.
   ``I put before you today a challenge _ a challenge to reject a
way of living which does not correspond to the best of your local
traditions and your Christian faith,'' said the pontiff, his white
robes flapping in the strong wind that swept the Army Air Wing
military airport.
   ``Many people in Africa look beyond Africa for the so-called
freedom of the modern way of life,'' he said. ``Today I urge you to
look inside yourselves. Look to the riches of your own traditions,
look to Christ.''
   The pontiff reiterated his plea for sustained assistance to the
640,000 refugees who have poured into Malawi fleeing civil war in
Mozambique.
   ``Every effort by the public authorities, the churches and
international organizations to help these brothers and sisters must
be encouraged and supported,'' he said.
   ``To you who have had to cross the border, I say: `Do not lose
hope.' ... We must all pray to increase peace and harmony in this
continent. The future of Africa is at stake.''
   At the departure ceremony earlier in Blantyre, the pope
expressed thanks for the ``truly African'' welcome he received in
Malawi, referring to the colorful dancing, singing and other native
customs displayed throughout the three-day stay.
   In farewell remarks to the pope, President-for-Life Hastings
Kamuzu Banda defended Malawi's record as the only black-ruled
African nation maintaining formal diplomatic ties with South Africa.
   ``I have always believed in seeing the world not as it should be
but as it is. ... Both of us believe in solving problems not by
violence and confrontation but through contact and dialogue,''
Banda said.
   Banda ended his speech by waving his elephant-hair fly whisk and
leading his personal troupe of women singers and dancers in
chanting, ``Long Live His Holiness the Pope, Long Live the Church.''
</TEXT>
