<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 1943EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Romania-Missiles     05-06 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Romania-Missiles,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Magazine: West German Firm Helps Build Romanian Missile Factory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romania is using technology
provided by a West German firm to build an assembly plant for
missiles that can carry nuclear warheads, the magazine Der Spiegel
said Saturday.
   The Hamburg-based news weekly said most of the rocket technology
for the Romanian factory came from the Messerschmitt-Boelkow-Blohm
company of Munich. It said MBB developed it in the mid-1980s for
Argentina.
   The report, which will appear in Der Spiegel's Monday edition,
was provided early to other news media. It said the Romanian plant
was being constructed partly underground and was intended to
manufacture what Der Spiegel said are ``Condor-2 rockets.''
   The report did not specify the location of the Romanian plant.
   On April 14, Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu publicly
stated that his country has the ability to make nuclear weapons,
but he said the communist nation had no intention of making use of
the technology.
   Western experts say there is no way to verify the claim
independently, but that it is doubtful because Romania apparently
has been unable to complete a largely imported nuclear power plant
under construction at Cernavoda on the Danube river.
   In a similar report on the rockets last week, Der Spiegel said
that MBB technology was being used to develop medium-range missiles
for Argentina, Egypt and Iraq with a range of 600 miles.
   Der Spiegel said MBB circumvented West German restrictions on
arms exports by selling the technology through a consortium of
small companies in Austria, Switzerland and West Germany.
   The articles follow similar reports by other West German news
media over the past month. Prosecutors have opened a probe of
several companies in West Germany, including some that are MBB
subsidiaries.
   MBB, a giant aerospace and armaments company, has said it does
not want to comment on the reports while the case is under
investigation.
</TEXT>
