<SECOND>AM-Kentucky Derby-Newspage,0182</SECOND>
<HEAD>Odds-on Favorite Beaten in Kentucky Derby</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sunday Silence, a horse twice rejected at
auction, took the lead on the final turn then held off heavily
favored Easy Goer to win the Kentucky Derby at a chilly Churchill
Downs on Saturday.
   Pat Valenzuela, winning his first Derby, got Sunday Silence to
the end of the 1\ miles in 2:05, 2{ lengths in front of Easy Goer.
Awe Inspiring was another head back and three-quarters of a length
in front of Dansil.
   It was the coldest Derby day in 72 years _ 43 degrees as the 15
3-year-olds burst out of the gate. It was 45 degrees in 1917, when
Omar Khayyam won.
   Sunday Silence twice was taken to auction, once as a yearling
and once as a 2-year-old, and twice bought back by his owners
because of lack of interest.
   The entry of Easy Goer and Awe Inspiring, who finished third,
had gone off as a 4-5 favorite. The previous odds-on choice for the
Derby was Spectacular Bid, who won in 1979.
