<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil-Drugs     05-06 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Drugs,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Lords Blamed for Killing Spanish Rancher Who Aided U.S. Agents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TODD LEWAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five gunmen ambushed and shot to
death a Spanish rancher who helped U.S. agents try to break a
marijuana-trafficking ring, a U.S. official said Saturday.
   Timothy L. Towel, U.S. ambassador to Paraguay, said the rancher
was killed at the order of drug lords.
   Domingo Martin Martin, a Spaniard who lived in the Paraguayan
state of Ambaya for 20 years, was slain in his car Thursday morning
shortly after entering the Brazilian border town of Ponta Pora,
Towel said in a telephone interview from Asuncion, Paraguay.
   Martin, 55, was heading to a soy bean silo he owned in the
nearby Brazilian town of Zansapyta. He had slowed his car in a busy
traffic circle when the five gunmen, armed with automatic weapons,
pulled up alongside him in a car and sprayed his vehicle with
bullets, the ambassador said.
   He said Martin was killed instantly with seven shots to the head
and one shotgun blast to the chest.
   The gunmen escaped into Paraguay, Towel said.
   ``Martin was assassinated by drug lords who resented that he was
heroically helping to stop drug trafficking between Paraguay and
Brazil,'' Towel said.
   The Spaniard had allowed U.S. and Paraguayan narcotics teams to
use his properties near the Paraguayan town of Pedro Juan
Caballero, about six miles south of Ponta Pora, as a base camp and
air strip, the ambassador said.
   Towel said the agents had found marijuana plantations in forests
on the Paraguayan side of the border.
   Jeff Brown, a spokesman for the U.S. Embassy in Paraguay, said
the anti-drug operation was to last two weeks. He said the drugs
were being smuggled into Brazil for local consumption.
   Federal police officials in Brasilia, the capital of Brazil,
said no one there was authorized to speak about the killing.
</TEXT>
