<FIRST>r a AM-MeatProtest     05-06 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Meat Protest,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Animal Rights Activists Oppose Sale of Exotic Meats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH HARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists opposed to the sale of game
animals marched Saturday outside a supermarket where rattlesnake,
deer, and bear meat were being offered in a test-marketing study.
   But the Illinois wholesaler who supplied the meats to the store
said they were healthful, none were from endangered species and he
didn't know ``what all the squawk is about.''
   About 20 sign-carrying protesters stood outside the Cub Foods
store on the city's west side, handed leaflets to passers-by, and
chanted, ``Don't shop Cub, give Big Bear a hug.''
   The chants referred to Big Bear, a rival grocery chain whose
slogan is ``Give' em a Big Bear hug.''
   ``What we want are the meats taken off the market,'' said Robin
Russell, director of Protect Our Earth's Treasures.
   ``What they're (Cub officials) trying to do is expand
exploitation of animals,'' he added. ``We want them to say the
market study is done and that's it.''
   Allan Roosz, meat department manager at the store, declined
comment. Telephone calls Saturday to Cub headquarters in
Stillwater, Minn., were not answered.
   Terry Wilhite, Ohio meat merchandiser for the grocery chain,
said the products came from Czimer Foods, a distributor in
Lockport, Ill. He said the market was the only Cub store in Ohio
offering such fare.
   The meats offered at Cub Foods ranged from deer at $7.99 a
pound, to whole rattlesnake for $14.99 each. Black bear shoulders
were priced at $9.99 a pound.
   Columbus Zoo Director Jack Hannah had called the store to
complain about its sale of giraffe meat, The Columbus Dispatch
reported Saturday. Cub Foods quit selling African game after
receiving complaints about such sales.
   Rudy Czimer, vice president and manager of wholesaling for
Czimer Foods, said in a telephone interview Saturday that protests
were nothing new to the family business his father began in 1914.
   ``This has been going on for years ... I get letters all the
time,'' Czimer said. ``I don't know what all the squawk is about.
   ``The animals are raised on game farms, and there's not anything
on the endangered or protected (species) lists. The government
watches us on that,'' he said, adding that Czimer Foods does not
raise the animals, but purchases them from ranches all over the
nation.

</TEXT>
