<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 2030EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TankerSpill     05-06 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tanker Spill,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Subcommittee To Probe Alaska Oil Spill</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill-Mate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional panel investigating the
nation's worst oil spill prepared Saturday for two days of
hearings, but the committee's chairman has already drawn a few
harsh conclusions.
   ``Oil companies have demonstrated they have no ability, no
expertise, no capability in cleaning up oil spills,'' Rep. George
Miller, D-Calif., said at a public meeting in the fishing town of
Cordova 50 miles from the spill site.
   Miller, chairman of the House Interior Committee's subcommittee
on water and energy, said Friday the spill ``is not just about
polluted waters, dead birds, otters. It's about disrupted
communities, families, lifestyles.''
   Miller's five-member panel has scheduled hearings for Sunday and
Monday in Valdez, near the section of Prince William Sound where
the tanker Exxon Valdez hit a reef March 24 and poured more than 10
million gallons of crude into the water. Members of the panel and
its 26-member staff continued arriving Saturday.
   The 987-foot tanker's former captain, Joseph Hazelwood, has been
accused of operating the ship while intoxicated, and faces a June
20 trial on misdemeanor charges. A grand jury is conducting a
felony investigation.
   Third Mate Gregory Cousins, who was at the helm when the wreck
occurred, said Hazelwood did not appear to be drunk at the time.
   ``There was no indication there was anything wrong,'' Cousins
said in a story in Saturday's editions of the Tampa (Fla.) Tribune.
He described Hazelwood as ``extremely competent.''
   Cousins has been on leave at home in Tampa preparing his
testimony for a National Transportation Safety Board hearing May 16
in Anchorage.
   Miller's panel will hear testimony from Coast Guard officers,
Exxon executives and environmentalists.
   Miller was quick to criticize not only oil companies but
Alyeska, the jointly owned pipeline service company in Valdez,
which is the terminus of the trans-Alaska pipeline from the North
Slope.
   ``Back in 1973, we made a compact with Alyeska and its owners,
including Exxon,'' Miller said. ```In exchange for the right to
drill for oil on public lands, (they promised) they'd do so in a
safe fashion.''
   But, he added, the oil company lobbied state and federal
officials to get the agreement changed to the industry's benefit.
``What we didn't know is that they'd spend the next 10 years
undermining that compact,'' he said.
   Exxon spokesman Karsten Rodvik said Saturday that he was not
aware of Miller's statements, and could not comment on them.
   In the more than six weeks since the spill, oil has fouled
beaches as far as 525 miles southwest of Valdez.
   The hardest hit areas include the islands within Prince William
Sound and beaches at Katmai National Park, a spectacular wildife
refuge on the Alaska Peninsula.
</TEXT>
