<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Crash 4thLd-Writethru   05-06 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Crash, 4th Ld-Writethru,a0578,0626</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Carrying U.S. Tourists Crash-Lands in Jungle; Six Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout with IDs of victims, survivors, comment from airline,
details of rescue, CORRECTS time of crash. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plane carrying American tourists lost
power in an engine and crash-landed in a remote jungle of the
Yucatan Peninsula, killing six people and injuring 10, officials
said Saturday.
   The Aerocozumel flight carrying 18 people was returning to the
resort island of Cozumel after taking the tourists to view ancient
Indian ruins at Chichen Itza, 115 miles west of Cozumel.
   It crashed at 2:30 p.m. Friday about two miles outside the Playa
del Carmen airport, about 125 miles northeast of Chichen Itza, the
airline said.
   Fifteen of the 16 tourists aboard were U.S. citizens and one was
a Canadian, according to airline representative Jaime Valenzuela.
   He identified one of the dead as Susan Montgomery, 42, of Canby,
Ore. He identified the others, whose hometowns and ages were not
available, as Guillermo and Margaret Salisbury, Pryor and Jayne
Hendricks, and Laura Chamberlain. All the dead were U.S. citizens.
   Valenzuela identified other surviving passengers as Gary
Anderson, Diana Len, Ross Blocksledye, Rosalyn Knobbs, Gilbert and
Sharon Barker, Catherine Wynne, Tony Knobbs, and Greg Chamberlain.
The other survivor was Glenn Robertson of Canada. Their hometowns
also were not available.
   Valenzuela said 10 injured people, including the pilot and tour
guide, were treated at Cancun's Social Security Institute Hospital.
He said none of the injuries were life-threatening. It was not
known who the two uninjured passengers were.
   Early reports had said up to 12 people were injured.
   The airline representative said the dead were being taken to the
Cancun morgue. U.S. consular representatives said they were working
on transporting the bodies back to the United States.
   Valenzuela said the 6-year-old, British-made Titalus Trislander
airplane was carrying the tourists under contract with Fiesta
Cozumel Holidays. He said it left Cozumel on Friday morning.
   Pilot Carlos Corso had 4,000 hours of flying time, the airline
representative said. He applauded the pilot's skill in bringing the
plane down without more deaths.
   The pilot radioed the Cancun airport tower when one of the
plane's three engines died. He crash-landed in thick jungle with
``very high, very thick'' growth up to 50 feet high, and search
planes found the plane about two hours later, Valenzuela said.
   However, helicopters were unable to land in the jungle, so
rescuers had to go in on foot.
   Red Cross worker Josefina Cardiel said the plane crashed inside
a ravine, and troops had to clear a path and provide rappelling
equipment so Red Cross workers could reach the plane.
   A rescue team of 70-90 people _ consisting of army, navy, Red
Cross personnel, and local residents _ hacked with machetes all
night, approaching the site about 6:30 a.m. Saturday, Valenzuela
said. They then cleared a spot for a helicopter to land.
   A navy helicopter ferried victims Saturday to a landing pad at
the Cancun hospital.
   Russ Knobbs, father of victim Susan Montgomery, said he and his
wife waited at the hospital hours before any helicopters landed.
   Knobbs, who had another daughter and a son on the flight, said
he and his wife suspected something was wrong when the plane didn't
come back as scheduled Friday afternoon.
   ``We had a pretty good inkling when they didn't return,'' he
said.
   Investigators were at the crash site to determine the cause,
said Capt. Rene Martinez, an Aerocozumel pilot.
   Chichen Izta is a large pre-Colombian archaeological site
popular with foreign tourists. Some of the city's buildings date
from 879 A.D.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
