<FIRST>u i AM-Panama 3rdLd-Writethru   05-06 0923</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0574,0951</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panamanians Brace For Presidential Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 10-13, `Murtha's delegation...McCain added' with
six grafs to UPDATE with activities of U.S. delegation, Carter. Pick up
14th pvs, `A U.S....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merchants boarded up their stores and
shoppers jammed supermarkets to stock up on non-perishable foods on
Saturday as Panamanians warily took precautions on the eve of a
presidential election.
   The vote Sunday has evolved into another showdown between Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega, the head of the Panamanian Defense Forces
and the country's de facto ruler, and the United States.
   Noriega, while stumping for his hand-picked candidate, claimed
that a vote for the opposition is a vote for U.S. control of this
Central American country.
   The opposition and U.S. officials charge that Noriega plans to
rig the vote to ensure the continuation of his iron-handed military
rule.
   Mindful of violent anti-Noriega disturbances a year ago that
shut down most businesses, some shop owners in the capital boarded
up their windows. People flocked to markets to stock up on items
such as rice and canned goods.
   A 13-member observer delegation appointed by President Bush
arrived in Panama City on an American government jet Saturday
afternoon despite Panamanian statements that the delegation would
not be welcome.
   Delegation members would not say if they had visas to enter the
country. Rep. John Murtha, D-Pa., heading the delegation, only
said, ``We have the appropriate documentation'' and declined to
answer further questions.
   The United States recognizes Eric Delvalle, who Noriega fired
last year, as Panama's legitimate president, and the current
government does not recognize visas issued by Panamanian consuls in
the United States, all of whom are still loyal to Delvalle.
   Panama has invited election observers from the European
Parliament and several Latin American and Caribbean countries and
has said uninvited delegations are unwelcome. But it has welcomed
an unofficial observer group that includes former presidents Jimmy
Carter and Gerald Ford.
   On Saturday, Carter toured the Panama Canal and discussed the
operation of the waterway.
   Murtha's delegation arrived at the U.S. Howard Air Force Base to
avoid the visa requirements and left in three military helicopters
for an undisclosed location, where they will stay.
   U.S. Embassy Spokesman Terence Kneebone said the delegation
hopes to split up into three groups to observe Sunday's voting and
plans to return to the United States on Monday.
   U.S. officials and a member of the delegation, all of whom spoke
on condition of anonymity, indicated the delegation was in Panama
on temporary orders from the U.S. Department of Defense, which
authorizes their presence without a visa at American military bases.
   It was not immediately known what, if any, access, the orders
might give them to the rest of Panama.
   But Maj. Edgardo Lopez, spokesman for the Panama Defense Forces,
said: ``I cannot go into the United States without a visa. They can
come into Panama without visas. This is a provocation.''
   A U.S. Southern Command official said Noriega's Defense Forces
set up checkpoints late Friday to control access into the former
Panama Canal Zone, where many U.S. military personnel live.
   U.S. personnel have had no problems leaving the former zone
area, despite the Panamanian checkpoints, the Southern Command
official said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The command, citing possible disturbances, planned to increase
security on Saturday. It previously had urged the estimated 12,000
American troops stationed in Panama to go into the capital only on
essential business.
   The canal zone once was controlled by the United States but was
among the areas that reverted to Panamanian control under the
Panama Canal treaties of 1977.
   Under the treaties, full control of the canal is to be turned
over to Panama in 1999. But the tense relations between Noriega and
Washington have complicated that treaty.
   The Bush administration, saying election fraud likely will
maintain Noriega's grip on power, said Friday it is considering
more measures to oust the military leader, including possibly
seizing his assets abroad.
   Although Panamanians will pick from two leading candidates, the
big issues have been Noriega's rule and Washington's influence on
Panamanian affairs.
   Pro-government candidate Carlos Duque said Friday the general
should remain as head of the Panamanian Defense Forces ``until the
year 2000'' to assure that Panama gets control of the Panama Canal.
   The eight parties in the pro-government National Liberation
Coalition contend that the opposition and the United States plan to
delay or cancel handing over the canal.
   Opposition presidential candidate Guillermo Endara has said he
will fire Noriega if the general won't retire, although Noriega has
installed and deposed presidents at will since he took control of
the armed forces in 1983.
   Endara is running for the five-year term under the banner of the
Democratic Opposition Alliance, a three-party coalition.
   The winner takes office Sept. 1.
   About 1.2 million of Panama's 2.2 residents are registered to
vote. Polls are open from 7 a.m. (8 a.m. EDT) to 5 p.m. The
government has promised results within 24 hours after polls close.
   In the last election, in 1984, Nicolas Ardito Barletta was
narrowly elected over Arnulfo Arias Madrid amid cries of fraud.
Noriega had Barletta resign and installed Eric Delvalle as
president in 1985.
   When Delvalle tried to fire Noriega in February 1988 after the
general was indicted in the United States on drug trafficking
charges, Noriega engineered Delvalle's ouster and installed Manuel
Solis Palma as acting president.
   Duque supporters have charged that the United States is spending
millions of dollars for the opposition campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
