<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Labor     05-06 0218</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Labor,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Centrist Politician Makes Cautious Overture To Labor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of Britain's squabbling political center
has made a cautious overture to the Labor Party, the main
opposition to the governing Conservatives, reports said Saturday.
   The remarks by Dr. David Owen, head of the Social Democratic
Party, follow the socialist Labor Party's upset victory over the
Conservatives in a special parliamentary election.
   He said in an interview with a Labor magazine, ``Enterprise of
Labor,'' that he would have ``no problems'' serving under Labor
leader Neil Kinnock in a coalition as long as some policies were
changed, the domestic Press Association agency reported.
   The Independent newspaper also carried excerpts from the
interview, which quoted Owen as saying Kinnock had done a
``remarkable job'' leading the party.
   But Kinnock's office issued a short rebuff, saying: ``No pacts.
No deals.'' Owen split with the main body of Social Democratic
Party members last year when they merged with the Liberal Party to
become the Social and Liberal Democratic Party.
   The Social and Liberal Democrats have 19 legislators in the
650-member House of Commons, while the Social Democrats have three,
compared with the Conservative Party's 374 and Labor's 228.
   In Thursday's parliamentary election, Labor won a seat in the
Vale of Glamoran that the Conservatives held for 38 years.
