<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 2235EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ArmySpy     05-06 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Army Spy,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Soldier-Spy Severely Damaged Electronic Listening Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army warrant officer court-martialed for
espionage may have critically damaged several electronic
surveillance operations aimed at the Soviet bloc, The New York
Times reported in Sunday editions.
   James W. Hall III rendered useless one program that had cost
hundreds of millions of dollars and was meant to exploit weak links
in the Soviet communications network, the Times said.
   ``Without commenting on the specifics, it appears that Hall did
very serious damage,'' Senate Intelligence Committee Chairman David
Boren, D-Okla., told the newspaper.
   ``We are looking at the potential _ and it's so far just
potential _ that this could be the Army's Walker case,'' one
official told the Times, referring to the espionage ring led by
former Navy officer John A. Walker Jr., who was arrested in 1985.
   Hall, 30, reportedly was recruited in 1982. He was arrested Dec.
20 and after pleading guilty to espionage in Feburary began a
40-year prison term.
   The Times said Hall, 30, was one of the highest-paid
Eastern-bloc spies, receiving $300,000 over a six-year span from
the Soviets and East Germany.
   The newspaper said prosecution documents at Hall's court-martial
said that Hall disclosed data on eavesdropping systems and
information about Western alliance plans in the event of a war in
Europe.
   The Times quoted unidentified sources as saying that Hall gave
East Germany or the Soviet Union NATO wartime scenarios well into
the 21st century.
   The newspaper said the United States first learned about Hall's
spying from a tip from a Central Intelligence Agency source inside
the East German government. The CIA source has defected to the West
and is in hiding.
   Few details on the nature of the information Hall relayed to his
agents had been released before.
   The Times said U.S. officials fear Hall may have been just one
of several American soldiers who were recruited by a 58-year-old
mechanic, Huseyin Yildirim, who taught auto repair to Army
personnel at Field Station Berlin, where Hall was posted.
</TEXT>
