<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Socialist Leader Speaks Out for More Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of this country's
Socialist Party has broken with the official Communist line in a
published speech calling for more democracy and independent
political parties.
   Socialist leader Jan Skoda, in a speech reported Friday by the
Svobodne Slovo daily, made a forceful plea for a stronger
parliament, independent parties, public referendums on major
issues, and academic freedom.
   Czechoslovakia's ruling Communists have curbed any independent
voice for the officially tolerated Socialists and other parties
since reforms were crushed in a Soviet-led Warsaw Pact invasion in
1968.
   The Communists have recently rejected calls for reforms from
democratic opposition groups that they brand as anti-Communist.
   ``Without substantial progress in the democratization of
political, social and economic life, we shall not manage to ...
gain the citizen's support for changes, whose implementation is the
only way to overcome problems the society has today,'' Skoda was
quoted as saying.
   Skoda's speech stressed, however, that he wants to work within
the system for change.
