<FIRST>r a AM-NuclearProtest     05-06 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Protest,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>59 Demonstrators Arrested Outside Nuke Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELLIOTT MINOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. MARYS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 59 anti-nuclear
demonstrators during a peaceful protest Saturday at a base in
southeast Georgia for submarines carrying the new Trident II
missiles.
   Sponsors said 300 protesters appeared outside Kings Bay Naval
Submarine Base, making it the largest of 28 demonstrations at
nuclear facilities around the country.
   Pax Christi, a national Roman Catholic peace group based in
Erie, Pa., organized the protests to mark the anniversary of a 1983
pastoral letter from U.S. Catholic bishops that opposed the
development of first-strike nuclear systems.
   ``We're trying to draw attention to the fact that the Trident
submarine ... is a major move ahead in the arms race,'' said
Auxilliary Bishop Thomas Gumbleton of Detroit. ``It's part of an
overall first-strike capability.''
   The USS Tennessee, the first of 10 Ohio-class subs that will
operate from Kings Bay, arrived in January. Each submarine will
carry 24 Trident II missiles.
   Navy Secretary William Ball III has described the new nuclear
submarines as the most significant weapon development since the
Polaris submarines were launched in 1960.
   The protesters gathered to hear speeches and music beneath a
clump of moss-covered oaks and pines near the base's front gate
before marching to the base.
   Those arrested, including a 79-year-old woman who carried a sign
that read, ``Granny for Peace,'' were cited for trespassing and
obstructing the road in front of the base, police said.
   Bruce Nelson, a spokesman for the Camden County Sheriff's
Department, said Saturday night that two demonstrators, who gave
their names as John and Jane Doe, were jailed on charges of refusal
to give their proper name. The others were released after being
given warning citations, he said.
</TEXT>
