<FIRST>r a AM-Spearfishing 2ndLd-Writethru a0563 05-06 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spearfishing, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0563,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede BOULDER JUNCTION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sports Anglers, Spearers in Confrontation At Wisconsin Lake</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with confrontation at boat landings;
picks up 4th graf pvs, `The arrests...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUTTERNUT, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sport fishermen shouted racial slurs at
nine boats full of Chippewa Indians, protected under treaty rights,
as they slipped into the waters of a northern lake to begin
spearfishing on Saturday.
   About a dozen Wisconsin Department of Natural Resources boats
cleared a path for the traditional spearfishing boats through
dozens of craft skippered by anti-treaty protesters at Butternut
Lake.
   The crowd protesting the Indians' right to spearfish on
off-reservation lakes was estimated at 1,000 people.
   The protesters shouted ``go home'' and racial epithets, and
ridiculed a group of Indians and their supporters who gathered
around a drum playing tribal music.
   Most of the tribal members stood silently, although some tried
to talk to the protesters.
   Police officers wearing riot helmets and face masks patrolled
the lakeshore to keep the protesters away from the boat landings.
   The natural resources department moved 90 percent of its
173-warden staff to northern Wisconsin to deal with the increased
number of boats expected on the water, said George Meyer, the
department's administrator of nforcement.
   More than a hundred opponents of the Chippewa's treaty rights
were arrested Friday on the eve of the sports fishing season when a
crowd crossed police lines at a Trout Lake boat landing.
   Butternut and Trout lakes are among a cluster of lakes in the
north woods of Wisconsin.
   The arrests were the most in a day since the tribe began
spearing fish on northern lakes five years ago under a court-upheld
guarantee of 19th century treaties that ceded much of northern
Wisconsin to the United States.
   Meyer said the protesters, who have run boats past the Indians
to disturb their spearing, are a small percentage of sport
fishermen.
   Spearfishing begins during spring spawning, ahead of the general
fishing season, and is regulated by the Indians. It is far more
efficient than traditional rod and reel fishing. As a result, the
state had to limit rod-and-reel catches of walleyed pike on 254
lakes.
   Al Soik, president of Stop Treaty Abuse Wisconsin, said
opponents of the treaty rights were waiting to see what action Gov.
Tommy Thompson would take.
   ``If he stops the spearing, there won't be any reason for us to
go out there,'' he said. ``If he doesn't, we'll be back.''
   The Republican governor tried unsuccessfully Friday to get U.S.
District Judge Barbara Crabb in Madison to order the end of
spearfishing before the action began. Thompson testified that
violence could erupt and could lead to deaths if both the Chippewa
and the state fishermen are allowed to fish on the same lakes.
   Crabb denied Thompson's request, saying she would not allow
``violent and lawless protests'' to interfere with the tribe's
rights. Thompson said the state would appeal.
   Meanwhile, hundreds of people gathered at the Lac du Flambeau
tribal center to show their support for Chippewa treaty rights.
Organizers said the group planned to counter demonstrations against
Chippewa spearing.
   Tom Maulson, a Lac du Flambeau tribal judge, said he did not
think the start of the general fishing season would worsen the
situation.
   ``These guys come up here to fish, they don't want to fight
Indians,'' he said.
</TEXT>
