<FIRST>r a AM-DowneyAd     05-05 0335</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Downey Ad,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trump Denies Authorizing Use Of His Name On Morton Downey Ad</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: 1st Amendment and peoples cq in 2nd graf as appeared in ad</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Developer Donald Trump and singer Robert
Goulet did not authorize the use of their names in an advertisement
appearing Friday in support of ``shock TV'' show host Morton Downey
Jr., a Trump spokeswoman said.
   A full-page advertisement in USA Today reads ``Burn Mort? Why
not just burn the Constitution. We believe in Mort ... We believe
in freedom.''
   The ad also said: ``Television is the peoples medium and the 1st
Amendment protects the rights of the Morton Downey Jr. Show and any
show, regardless of its content.''
   Among the 25 names that appear at the bottom of the ad are
Trump, Goulet, Harvard law professor Allen Dershowitz and Broadway
producer Jerry Cohen.
   Downey's show, known for his confrontations with guests, has
suffered a ratings collapse in recent months, and several stations
have canceled the program because of decreased ratings, lack of
advertiser support or consumer complaints.
   Last month, Downey reported that he had been attacked at San
Francisco International Airport by neo-Nazi skinheads, who he said
cut off his hair and painted a reverse swastika on his face. But
authorities could not verify the story and some dismissed it as a
publicity stunt.
   Trump is upset about the ad because he did not give anyone
permission to use his name, said his secretary Norma Foerderer.
   ``He thinks it's horrible and unfortunate,'' that someone used
his name, she said in a telephone interview from the developer's
New York office. ``(But) he certainly supports the First
Amendment.''
   Ms. Foerderer said she received a call Friday from Goulet, who
also was upset at the unauthorized use of his name.
   Calls to Downey's New York office for comment were not returned.
   Rachel McAllister, a spokeswoman for Downey's public relations
Los Angeles-based firm, Schecter, Cone and McAllister, said, ``All
the people listed on the ad contributed to it.''
</TEXT>
