<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     05-06 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0730</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House says President Bush and West
German Chancellor Helmut Kohl have failed in their latest round of
long-distance diplomacy to resolve major differences over nuclear
weapons in Europe.
   Bush and Kohl spoke by telephone for 20 minutes Friday about the
West German's proposal to soon open East-West talks on eliminating
short-range nuclear weapons in Europe. The White House said Bush
was unchanged in his opposition to such negotiations.
   The dispute between Bonn and Washington on short-range nuclear
weapons _ missiles and artillery shells _ threatens to mar the
harmony of a NATO summit scheduled May 29-30 in Brussels.
   The United States opposes any negotiations on grounds that NATO
needs nuclear weapons to compensate for the overwhelming
superiority of Soviet-bloc tanks, artillery, soldiers and other
conventional forces.
   ``The United States posture has not changed,'' White House press
secretary Marlin Fitzwater said after the telephone call. ``It does
not appear that a basis for agreement is there, but we'll continue
to discuss it and see.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic church and
international observers led by two former U.S. presidents urged
Panamanians to vote peacefully and asked the government to conduct
free and fair presidential elections Sunday.
   About 1.1 million Panamanians are registered to vote in an
election that also will pick two vice presidents, a 67-member
National Assembly and 510 municipal council members.
   Relations between Panama and the United States _ strained over
the confrontation between the U.S. government and strongman Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega _ are the main issues in the campaign.
   President Bush and Panama's domestic opposition have claimed the
government plans to rig the elections to gain victory for its
candidate, Carlos Duque, a close business associate of Noriega who
is backed by an eight-party pro-government coalition.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The foreman of the Oliver North jury says the
jurors were caught in ``a war between the Democrats and the
Republicans'' and should have received the testimony of President
Bush and former President Reagan.
   Nevertheless, ``I think it was a fair trial,'' Denise Anderson,
34, told reporters at a news conference in her living room Friday,
24 hours after the jury convicted North of three Iran-Contra
charges and acquitted him of nine others.
   Asked whether the trial was fair even though Reagan was not
called to testify about the events that shook his second White
House term, Ms. Anderson said, ``It was fair to a certain degree.''
   ``I feel as though Reagan, and I could go on to elaborate on who
else, should have been down there,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI agent who sued the bureau for
denying him promotions believes the door is open for him and other
Hispanics to advance, but Bernardo M. ``Mat'' Perez concedes the
door had to be kicked down.
   ``We, Hispanics, as any other American citizens, have a
contribution to make and we want to believe in the American
system,'' he said after a federal judge ordered changes in the
agency's promotional system and established a procedure for
promoting Hispanics wrongly denied advancement.
   ``All we want is an equal chance. Now we're going to get it.''
   Because Hispanics do the same jobs as other FBI agents, they
deserve to obtain management positions, the 25-year veteran said.
   U.S. District Judge Lucius Bunton, after ruling in September
that the FBI discriminated against Hispanics, ordered a special
panel to be appointed to evaluate the claims of other Hispanic
agents in the class-action suit that they lost promotions.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh is
threatening to end the American Bar Association's role in screening
prospective federal judges unless it agrees not to consider
political or ideological beliefs.
   The ABA's Standing Committee on Federal Judiciary would no
longer screen prospective nominees unless the bar group keeps a
commitment that it made to made to Thornburgh, says David Runkel, a
senior aide to the attorney general.
   The ABA denies it made such a commitment.
   As he left the Justice Department on Friday night, Thornburgh
said ``we expect them to honor'' an agreement to revert to pre-1980
language in the ABA's judicial screening guidelines.
