<DOCNO> AP890506-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-06-89 0704EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-Unisys Adv08   05-06 0772</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Unisys, Adv 08,0798</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv08</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday May 8 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Unisys Sees Big Gains In Future</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. faces a defense-contracting
scandal and a quarterly loss, but the nation's third-biggest
computer company isn't talking about trouble. Instead, its chairman
wants to double revenue to $20 billion in five years.
   ``The arithmetic is not so difficult to fathom,'' W. Michael
Blumenthal said of his plans. ``If we can achieve double-digit
growth in the next several years, it will go a good distance toward
achieving that goal.''
   Investors don't have much faith in the growth plan, but
Blumenthal, 63, has defied the odds before, starting when he fled
with his family from Nazi Germany and survive the Japanese bombing
of Shanghai.
   Blumenthal, who still speaks with a German accent, earned a
doctorate from Princeton University and became Secretary of the
Treasury in the Carter administration. In 1986, as chairman of
Burroughs Corp., he engineered the $4.8 billion purchase of Sperry
Corp. to create Unisys.
   The modest success of Unisys has quieted skeptics who said the
merger of two old, slow-growing makers of incompatible mainframe
computers would never work.
   Bigness is important to Blumenthal because he believes it gives
the company credibility against International Business Machines
Corp., the biggest computer maker. Digital Equipment Corp. is
second.
   Blumenthal says he is hoping to achieve his growth goal through
acquisitions as well as internal expansion, especially in the
rapidly growing field of ``open systems'' _ computers that can run
a wider variety of programs.
   A measure of investors' skepticism is that Unisys' stock price
is less than eight times last year's per-share earnings, compared
with a ratio for IBM of more than 11.
   ``The market is valuing this company as if this growth strategy
will fail,'' said Donald Young, an analyst for Sanford C. Bernstein
&amp; Co. That assessment, he said, might be slightly harsh.
   A prolonged suspension by the Navy, brought about by the
investigation of the Pentagon procurement scandal, ``Operation Ill
Wind,'' has slowed progress toward that goal.
   Two former executives and two former consultants who worked for
Unisys have pleaded guilty in the case, which involves bribes paid
to Pentagon officials to win contracts.
   In March, three divisions of Unisys were barred indefinitely
from bidding on Navy contracts. Unisys is negotiating a monetary
settlement with the Justice Department that could lead to the Navy
allowing it to resume bidding.
   Financial analysts are estimating the Navy suspension will be
lifted soon, possibly sometime this summer. But they also say there
could be further indictments before the case is done.
   ``I get the impression the worst is yet to come,'' Young said.
   Unisys has been lucky so far in that few new contracts have been
put up for bid, and the company is continuing to do business under
old ones, said Curt Hessler, Unisys' chief financial officer. He
said the financial effect has been minor.
   The executives and the three suspended businesses were part of
the old Sperry. Unisys executives claim those convicted were
``rotten apples'' employed by a company now under new management.
   ``It was a rarity within Sperry and a rarity within the industry
and they deserve what they get,'' Hessler said of the former
executives.
   Blumenthal is confident an internal investigation that resulted
in the departure of 17 executives and the cancellation of contracts
with 60 consultants has rid the company of corruption.
   ``It's behind us. In a sense, it isn't our problem,'' he said.
   For Blumenthal, the company's other glaring problem _ a $78.7
million loss in the first quarter _ is also in the past.
   Blumenthal said the loss was due mostly to the rough transition
to a new mainframe computer line. The 2200 series of mainframes was
not available when expected and customers stopped buying the model
it replaced _ the 1100.
   But demand has been strong since the 2200 became available late
in the first quarter, Blumenthal said. Analysts agree that Unisys
will return to profitability in the current quarter.
   To achieve $20 billion in revenue, Blumenthal is focusing on
open systems _ or computers that can use different kinds of
software, not just the programs sold by, for instance, Unisys.
   The strategy is to grow at single-digit rates in older
businesses, keeping up with the industry pace, while gaining market
share in the fast-growing market for open systems based on Unix
software.
   Blumenthal also sees a consolidation that will have Unisys
acquiring smaller companies that can help it grow in networking,
software, telecommunications and professional services.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday, May 8</NOTE>
